<SYNC Start=4170><P Class=KRCC>
불과 열의 사용법을 터득한 것은<br>
인류 문명 최대의 업적으로 일컬어진다
<SYNC Start=10103><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=12674><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 냉기의 정복도<br>
그에 못지 않은 장엄한 여정이다
<SYNC Start=16382><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=16559><P Class=KRCC>
그 시작은 어두웠으나, 마침내<br>
첨단의 극저온 기술에 이르렀다
<SYNC Start=20723><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=22086><P Class=KRCC>
과거 수 세기 동안<br>
냉기는 곤혹스러운 수수께끼였다
<SYNC Start=25691><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=25872><P Class=KRCC>
누구도 그 실체를 이해하지 못했으며
<SYNC Start=28221><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=28457><P Class=KRCC>
이것을 이용한다는 것은<br>
더욱 힘들었다
<SYNC Start=31605><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=32219><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 최근 100년간, 냉기는<br>
인간의 일과 생활을 바꾸어놓았다
<SYNC Start=37754><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=38686><P Class=KRCC>
냉장고와 냉동식품이 없는<br>
가정이나 슈퍼마켓,
<SYNC Start=42654><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=42918><P Class=KRCC>
냉방 시설이 없는 고층 건물,
<SYNC Start=45197><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=45386><P Class=KRCC>
액체 산소를 이용하지 못하는 병원은<br>
상상도 할 수 없게 되었다
<SYNC Start=49356><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=51406><P Class=KRCC>
지금은 당연하게 여겨지는<br>
냉기를 다루는 기술 덕분에
<SYNC Start=54311><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=54492><P Class=KRCC>
밖으로는 우주를 탐사하고, 안으로는<br>
우리의 뇌를 들여다볼 수 있게 되었다
<SYNC Start=59667><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=60666><P Class=KRCC>
또한, 최첨단 극저온 기술을 통한<br>
양자 컴퓨터와 고속 네트워크는
<SYNC Start=66910><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=67017><P Class=KRCC>
인간이 사고하고 교류하는 방식마저<br>
변화시키게 될 수도 있다
<SYNC Start=71415><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=73918><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 지난 4세기에 걸쳐<br>
과학자와 몽상가들이
<SYNC Start=78975><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=79248><P Class=KRCC>
점점 더 낮은 온도를<br>
만들어내기 위해 뛰어들어
<SYNC Start=82795><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=82912><P Class=KRCC>
냉기를 정복하고<br>
우리의 삶을 풍요롭게 하며
<SYNC Start=85900><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=86043><P Class=KRCC>
나아가 저온의 궁극적인 한계에<br>
도전한 이야기이다
<SYNC Start=89146><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=89421><P Class=KRCC>
빛의 속도만큼이나 따라잡기 힘든,<br>
성배와도 같은 이 한계점은
<SYNC Start=93402><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=93650><P Class=KRCC>
절대 영도이다
<SYNC Start=96126><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=100542><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=yellow>절대 영도 - 1부: 냉기를 정복하다<br>
(2007.7.24 BBC Four)</font>
<SYNC Start=107162><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=109979><P Class=KRCC>
극한의 추위는 인간의 상상력에서<br>
늘 특별한 자리를 차지했다
<SYNC Start=114714><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=114980><P Class=KRCC>
오랜 세월 동안, 추위는<br>
죽음과 어둠을 몰고 다니는
<SYNC Start=118055><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=118196><P Class=KRCC>
사악한 힘으로 여겨졌다
<SYNC Start=120786><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=121081><P Class=KRCC>
냉기는 설명할 수 없는 현상이었다
<SYNC Start=124133><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=126441><P Class=KRCC>
그것은 과연 물질인가, 과정인가,<br>
아니면 어떤 특별한 존재인가?
<SYNC Start=130967><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=131470><P Class=KRCC>
17세기에는 아무도 알지 못했다
<SYNC Start=134123><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=134328><P Class=KRCC>
그래도 런던의 쌀쌀한 겨울 날씨에서<br>
냉기의 영향만큼은 확실히 느껴졌다
<SYNC Start=138493><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=141717><P Class=KRCC>
17세기 영국은 소위 소빙기(小氷期)<font color=violet>*</font>의<br>
한복판에 있었습니다<br>
<font color=violet>* 16~19세기 북반구 기온이 낮아졌던 시기</font>
<SYNC Start=144959><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=145057><P Class=KRCC>
요즘 기준으로는<br>
환상적으로 추운 날씨였죠
<SYNC Start=147317><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=147415><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>사이먼 샤퍼 - 케임브리지 대학</font><br>
불이 아니었다면 대부분의 사람들에게<br>
거의 언제나 추운 세상이었죠
<SYNC Start=152125><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=152345><P Class=KRCC>
추위는 그 자체로<br>
어떤 실재감을 주었고,
<SYNC Start=155601><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=155699><P Class=KRCC>
사람들이 느낄 수 있고<br>
실체가 있는 존재처럼 보였습니다
<SYNC Start=159735><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=160156><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 고대 그리스의<br>
아리스토텔레스 이래로 이어진
<SYNC Start=164930><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=165021><P Class=KRCC>
자연철학의 가장 정통적인 견해와<br>
잘 들어맞았습니다
<SYNC Start=170509><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=170847><P Class=KRCC>
그것은, 열과 냉기라는<br>
두 존재가 있다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=174961><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=175330><P Class=KRCC>
둘의 기능은 대칭적이죠
<SYNC Start=177753><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=178030><P Class=KRCC>
서로 합쳐질수도, 나눠질수도 있습니다
<SYNC Start=181026><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=184020><P Class=KRCC>
그때의 사람들은<br>
추위에 손쓸 도리가 없었다
<SYNC Start=187527><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=188248><P Class=KRCC>
자연의 힘을 신의 행위로 간주하며<br>
두려워하던 시대였기 때문이다
<SYNC Start=193646><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=195995><P Class=KRCC>
감히 냉기를 가지고 장난치는 사람은<br>
스스로 위험을 감수해야만 했다
<SYNC Start=201111><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=201953><P Class=KRCC>
이를 최초로 시도한 사람은<br>
연금술사 코넬리우스 드레블이었다
<SYNC Start=206132><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=208452><P Class=KRCC>
1620년 어느 더운 여름날,<br>
제임스 1세 왕과 그의 측근들이
<SYNC Start=212859><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=212918><P Class=KRCC>
기상천외한 사건을<br>
체험하기 위해 도착했다
<SYNC Start=216546><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=218545><P Class=KRCC>
궁정 마술사이기도 했던 드레블은
<SYNC Start=221544><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=221590><P Class=KRCC>
여름을 겨울로 둔갑시켜 보이겠다며<br>
왕에게 호언장담했다
<SYNC Start=226126><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=226468><P Class=KRCC>
그는 실내 공간으로는<br>
영국 제도에서 가장 큰 곳인
<SYNC Start=230460><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=230595><P Class=KRCC>
웨스트민스터 홀의 공기를<br>
냉각시킬 계획이었다
<SYNC Start=234821><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=238690><P Class=KRCC>
드레블은 왕을 뼛속까지<br>
벌벌 떨게 만들 심산이었다
<SYNC Start=241908><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=245102><P Class=KRCC>
그는 놀랄만큼 창의력이 풍부한<br>
빼어난 발명가였습니다
<SYNC Start=249005><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=249350><P Class=KRCC>
연금술, 영구기관,<br>
시간, 공간, 행성, 달, 태양, 신, ..
<SYNC Start=254711><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=254732><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>앤드류 쉬들로</font><br>
이런 주제에 깊이 몰두해 있었죠
<SYNC Start=258782><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=259042><P Class=KRCC>
열렬한 종교인이었구요
<SYNC Start=260980><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=261194><P Class=KRCC>
그는 자연 속에서 셀수없이 많은<br>
가능성을 찾아냈던 사람이었습니다
<SYNC Start=269024><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=271355><P Class=KRCC>
평생 드레블에 대해 큰 흥미를 가졌던<br>
화학자 앤드류 쉬들로 박사는
<SYNC Start=275424><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=275603><P Class=KRCC>
이 뛰어난 궁정 마술사의 마법을<br>
직접 재현해 보려고 한다
<SYNC Start=279517><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=281445><P Class=KRCC>
대부분의 연금술사들처럼,<br>
드레블은 트릭을 공개하지 않았다
<SYNC Start=284883><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=285200><P Class=KRCC>
쉬들로는 드레블이 인공 추위를 만들어낸<br>
수법에 대한 자신의 추측을 시험하려 한다
<SYNC Start=290656><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=296744><P Class=KRCC>
드레블이 최대한 낮은 온도를<br>
만들어내려고 시도했을 때
<SYNC Start=299379><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=299488><P Class=KRCC>
그는 일반적으로 얻을 수 있는<br>
최저 온도는 얼음이라는걸 알았습니다
<SYNC Start=304058><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=304276><P Class=KRCC>
얼음을 다른 종류의 소금과 섞으면<br>
더 낮은 온도까지 내려간다는 사실도
<SYNC Start=308818><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=308998><P Class=KRCC>
경험적으로 알고 있었을 것입니다
<SYNC Start=311508><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=312297><P Class=KRCC>
소금은 물의 어는점을<br>
낮추는 효과가 있다
<SYNC Start=316141><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=316497><P Class=KRCC>
쉬들로 박사는 드레블이 소금을 이용하여<br>
온도를 떨어뜨렸을거라고 추측한다
<SYNC Start=322654><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=325341><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 소금과 얼음만으로는<br>
그 넓은 공간의 기온을 낮추기엔 역부족이다
<SYNC Start=330194><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=330521><P Class=KRCC>
드레블은 정교한 기계장치를<br>
만드는 솜씨로 유명했다
<SYNC Start=334222><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=334402><P Class=KRCC>
쉬들로 박사는 드레블이 사용했을<br>
장치에 대한 아이디어를 갖고 있다
<SYNC Start=339947><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=342154><P Class=KRCC>
여기 이렇게 송풍기를 달아서
<SYNC Start=346039><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=346115><P Class=KRCC>
따뜻한 공기를<br>
이 차가운 용기 위로 보냅니다
<SYNC Start=350645><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=350844><P Class=KRCC>
공기가 차가운 용기 위를 지나면서
<SYNC Start=354541><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=354626><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 사실상 세계 최초의<br>
에어컨이 되는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=360056><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=362702><P Class=KRCC>
하지만, 정말 이것으로<br>
여름을 겨울로 바꿀 수 있었을까?
<SYNC Start=366051><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=367537><P Class=KRCC>
단 5초만에 최대한 잘 섞어야 합니다
<SYNC Start=373140><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=374500><P Class=KRCC>
쉬들로 박사는<br>
이 혼합물 용기들을 쌓아서
<SYNC Start=377536><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=377683><P Class=KRCC>
공기가 이 차가운 구간을<br>
통과하게 하려고 한다
<SYNC Start=380959><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=385982><P Class=KRCC>
공기가 아주 차갑네요
<SYNC Start=387591><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=387881><P Class=KRCC>
찬 공기가 손에 떨어지는 것을<br>
느낄 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=392135><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=392314><P Class=KRCC>
찬 공기가 따뜻한 공기보다<br>
무거우니까요
<SYNC Start=395290><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=395370><P Class=KRCC>
손의 감촉으로<br>
확실하게 느껴집니다
<SYNC Start=398351><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=401414><P Class=KRCC>
과연, 따뜻한 바람이<br>
지나가면서 차가워질 것인가?
<SYNC Start=406278><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=412366><P Class=KRCC>
커버를 두장째 벗겨내니까<br>
확실히 찬바람이 와 닿는군요
<SYNC Start=418680><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=419097><P Class=KRCC>
현재 온도 14도입니다
<SYNC Start=422078><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=422659><P Class=KRCC>
계속 해 주세요.<br>
지금 잘 하고 있어요
<SYNC Start=425489><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=426037><P Class=KRCC>
아마 아직도 좀더..
<SYNC Start=429530><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=435402><P Class=KRCC>
인공적인 추위를 경험한<br>
왕의 반응은 어땠을까?
<SYNC Start=439628><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=440653><P Class=KRCC>
깜짝 놀랐겠죠.<br>
어찌된 영문인지 몰랐을 겁니다
<SYNC Start=442906><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=443092><P Class=KRCC>
신이나 악마의 힘을 빌린건 아닐까<br>
하는 의문을 가졌을 법도 합니다
<SYNC Start=451080><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=451234><P Class=KRCC>
말 그대로 오싹한 한기를 느끼며<br>
황급히 자리를 뜨지 않았을까요
<SYNC Start=455540><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=456827><P Class=KRCC>
드레블이 그 방법에 대해<br>
기록해 두었더라면
<SYNC Start=459302><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=459408><P Class=KRCC>
냉방 기술의 발명자로<br>
역사에 기록되었을 것이다
<SYNC Start=462737><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=462970><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 이 아이디어는<br>
3세기가 지나서야 다시 빛을 보았다
<SYNC Start=468021><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=469281><P Class=KRCC>
냉기를 파악하고 정복하기 위해서는<br>
전혀 새로운 사고방식이 필요했다
<SYNC Start=475309><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=477543><P Class=KRCC>
제임스 왕 밑의 대법관이었던<br>
프랜시스 베이컨은
<SYNC Start=480224><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=480331><P Class=KRCC>
과학적 방법론을 구사하여<br>
열과 냉기를 연구한 최초의 인물이다
<SYNC Start=484738><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=485009><P Class=KRCC>
그는 고대로부터 내려오는<br>
지식을 답습하는 대신
<SYNC Start=489448><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=489627><P Class=KRCC>
실험을 하고 그 결과를 분석하는<br>
연구 방법의 중요성을 깨달았다
<SYNC Start=493449><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=494612><P Class=KRCC>
프랜시스 베이컨에게, 열과 냉기는<br>
세계관의 핵심에 놓인 문제였습니다
<SYNC Start=501429><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=501668><P Class=KRCC>
열과 냉기가 인간에게 얼마나 중요한지<br>
생각해 보면 그 까닭을 알 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=509238><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=509406><P Class=KRCC>
17세기에는 특히나<br>
두 가지 이유로 중요했는데
<SYNC Start=512082><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=512276><P Class=KRCC>
날씨, 그리고 질병입니다
<SYNC Start=515238><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=515860><P Class=KRCC>
사실 일상생활에서 보면,<br>
따뜻함이 건강에 주는 영향과
<SYNC Start=519266><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=519464><P Class=KRCC>
차가움이 건강에 주는 영향 사이의<br>
팽팽한 긴장이 존재합니다
<SYNC Start=523844><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=524305><P Class=KRCC>
따뜻함은 건강을 유지시켜 줍니다.<br>
생기가 달아나 버리지 않게 돕죠
<SYNC Start=532320><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=532745><P Class=KRCC>
그런데, 차가움도 죽음에 맞서는<br>
중요한 역할을 합니다
<SYNC Start=537819><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=538017><P Class=KRCC>
차갑게 유지되는 물질은<br>
썩지 않고 오래 보존되지요
<SYNC Start=541296><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=541370><P Class=KRCC>
물론 프랜시스 베이컨의 육체도<br>
예외는 아니겠죠
<SYNC Start=544996><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=548968><P Class=KRCC>
베이컨은 자신이 직접<br>
실험을 하는 경우는 드물었다
<SYNC Start=551924><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=552109><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 그 몇 안되는 실험 중 하나가<br>
그에게 불행을 가져다 주었다
<SYNC Start=557590><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=558582><P Class=KRCC>
그는 방금 잡은 닭에<br>
얼음과 눈을 채워서
<SYNC Start=562862><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=563052><P Class=KRCC>
닭고기가 얼마나 오래<br>
신선하게 보존되는지 조사했다
<SYNC Start=567260><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=568979><P Class=KRCC>
그 결과는 놀라웠다
<SYNC Start=570756><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=571093><P Class=KRCC>
닭고기는 며칠간이나<br>
신선하게 유지된 것이다
<SYNC Start=573925><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=574173><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 불운하게도,<br>
추위에 몸을 내맡긴 탓에
<SYNC Start=578298><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=578518><P Class=KRCC>
그는 폐렴에 걸리고 말았다
<SYNC Start=580470><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=582057><P Class=KRCC>
베이컨은 병상에서 죽어 가며
<SYNC Start=584634><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=584714><P Class=KRCC>
냉기에 대한 호기심의 대가가<br>
그의 목숨이었음을 깨달았다
<SYNC Start=589147><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=594500><P Class=KRCC>
그의 실험은 아이러니한<br>
비극으로 끝났지만,
<SYNC Start=600081><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=600277><P Class=KRCC>
얼음이나 눈의 냉장 효과를 실험하려는<br>
후학들의 열의는 꺾이지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=606971><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=608210><P Class=KRCC>
베이컨의 뒤를 따른 학자들은
<SYNC Start=610905><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=610977><P Class=KRCC>
운동, 열, 냉기 등을<br>
종합적으로 이해할 수 있다면
<SYNC Start=617011><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=617095><P Class=KRCC>
인간을 질병에서 해방시키고<br>
자연의 비밀을 풀게 될거라고 확신했습니다
<SYNC Start=621289><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=625493><P Class=KRCC>
"냉기란 무엇인가?"<br>
이 근본적인 질문은
<SYNC Start=628836><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=628979><P Class=KRCC>
베이컨이 사망한 이듬해에 태어난<br>
로버트 보일을 사로잡았다
<SYNC Start=632989><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=633327><P Class=KRCC>
부유한 귀족인 초대 코크 백작의<br>
아들이었던 그는
<SYNC Start=635881><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=636080><P Class=KRCC>
사비를 들여 값비싼 실험실을<br>
차릴 수 있었다
<SYNC Start=639947><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=642641><P Class=KRCC>
보일은 공기의 성질에 대한<br>
실험으로 유명하지만
<SYNC Start=645854><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=646049><P Class=KRCC>
냉기의 비밀을 터득한<br>
최초의 학자이기도 했다
<SYNC Start=649267><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=649534><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 중요성에 비해 외면받은 주제라고<br>
판단한 그는, 수많은 관련 실험을 했다
<SYNC Start=655409><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=658400><P Class=KRCC>
그는 냉기의 정체에 대한 관념들을<br>
매우 체계적으로 검증했습니다
<SYNC Start=665612><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=665820><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 공기로부터 나오는가?
<SYNC Start=668184><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=668535><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 빛의 부재에 기인한 것인가?
<SYNC Start=671663><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=671858><P Class=KRCC>
냉기를 불러일으키는 특이한 입자<br>
같은 것들이 존재하는 것인가?
<SYNC Start=679532><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=684260><P Class=KRCC>
보일은 그 시대의 가장 유력한<br>
견해를 공박했는데
<SYNC Start=687803><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=688080><P Class=KRCC>
어떤 견해이냐면, 냉기는<br>
어떤 근원적인 물질이라는 생각입니다
<SYNC Start=694049><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=694305><P Class=KRCC>
즉, 몸이 이 물질을 빨아들이면<br>
체온이 떨어지고
<SYNC Start=700256><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=700533><P Class=KRCC>
이를 방출하면<br>
체온이 올라간다는거죠
<SYNC Start=703391><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=704048><P Class=KRCC>
그는 이 관점이 틀렸다고 생각하고,<br>
실험을 통해 반증하려고 했습니다
<SYNC Start=709193><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=715184><P Class=KRCC>
보일은 물이 얼 때 부피가 늘어나는<br>
현상에 대해 의문을 가지고
<SYNC Start=719429><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=719857><P Class=KRCC>
부피가 늘어나면서 무게도 함께<br>
증가하는지 알아보려고 했다
<SYNC Start=725006><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=727574><P Class=KRCC>
물을 채운 통의 무게를 정확히 잰 다음<br>
눈밭으로 가지고 나가서
<SYNC Start=732030><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=732633><P Class=KRCC>
밤새 얼게 했다
<SYNC Start=735116><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=738042><P Class=KRCC>
보일은, 물이 얼음이 되었을 때<br>
무게가 늘어난다면
<SYNC Start=742777><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=742975><P Class=KRCC>
아마도 냉기가 물질임을 보여주는<br>
근거가 될거라고 추론했다
<SYNC Start=746902><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=747687><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 무게를 재어 보니<br>
조금도 차이가 없었다
<SYNC Start=752270><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=755518><P Class=KRCC>
이를 보고 보일이 추측한 것은
<SYNC Start=758255><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=758296><P Class=KRCC>
팽창이란 것은 물의 입자들이<br>
점점 거리를 넓힌 것이지,
<SYNC Start=762940><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=763243><P Class=KRCC>
외부에서 물질이 유입되는게<br>
아니라는 논리였습니다
<SYNC Start=769578><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=772640><P Class=KRCC>
보일은 냉기가 물질이 아니라<br>
입자들에 일어나는 일종의 현상이라는
<SYNC Start=777043><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=777068><P Class=KRCC>
생각을 갈수록 굳히게 되었다
<SYNC Start=780085><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=780290><P Class=KRCC>
그는 이전에 했던<br>
공기 펌프 실험을 상기했다
<SYNC Start=784078><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=786144><P Class=KRCC>
보일은 용기에 든 공기 입자들이<br>
탄성이 있어서 튕긴다고 생각했습니다
<SYNC Start=793043><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=793227><P Class=KRCC>
공기를 압축하면<br>
반발한다는 것이죠
<SYNC Start=795921><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=796095><P Class=KRCC>
이러한 생각은 열과 냉기에 대한<br>
그의 연구와도 깊은 연관이 있습니다
<SYNC Start=802917><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=803254><P Class=KRCC>
공기와 같은 물질은<br>
온도가 올라가면 팽창하는데,
<SYNC Start=809195><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=809462><P Class=KRCC>
그는 공기 입자를 아주 작은 용수철에<br>
비유하여 이를 설명했습니다
<SYNC Start=816129><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=816310><P Class=KRCC>
온도가 올라가면 용수철이 풀리면서<br>
더 많은 공간을 차지하니까 공기는 팽창합니다
<SYNC Start=821599><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=822460><P Class=KRCC>
열은 특정한 형태의 운동이라는게<br>
보일의 결론이었습니다
<SYNC Start=829542><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=830012><P Class=KRCC>
따라서 물질이 냉각되면<br>
운동은 줄어들겠죠
<SYNC Start=835162><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=837898><P Class=KRCC>
가장 오래 출간된 보일의 저서는<br>
냉기에 대한 책이었다
<SYNC Start=840998><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=841141><P Class=KRCC>
그럼에도 불구하고 이 주제는<br>
무척이나 난해했던지,
<SYNC Start=844760><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=844933><P Class=KRCC>
보일은 자신이 마치<br>
의료 도구나 의약품도 없이
<SYNC Start=848985><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=849057><P Class=KRCC>
머나먼 땅에서 일하는 의사가 된<br>
심정이라고 토로하기도 했다
<SYNC Start=852797><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=855178><P Class=KRCC>
이 머나먼 동토에서 일하는데 있어
<SYNC Start=858043><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=858221><P Class=KRCC>
그가 갈급히 원했던 중요한 도구는<br>
정확한 온도계였다
<SYNC Start=863659><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=877558><P Class=KRCC>
17세기 중반이 되어서야
<SYNC Start=879814><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=879883><P Class=KRCC>
피렌체의 유리 가공업자들이<br>
정확히 조정된 온도계를 만들어냈다
<SYNC Start=884839><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=885216><P Class=KRCC>
이제 온도의 측정이<br>
가능해진 것이다
<SYNC Start=889261><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=892238><P Class=KRCC>
수은 대신 그보다 가벼운<br>
알코올을 사용했기 때문에
<SYNC Start=896111><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=896346><P Class=KRCC>
그들이 만든 온도계 중에는<br>
길이가 몇미터에 이르거나
<SYNC Start=899325><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=899508><P Class=KRCC>
나선형으로 꼬인 것들도 많았다
<SYNC Start=902095><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=903669><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 아직도, 모든 온도계에는<br>
하나의 커다란 문제점이 있었다
<SYNC Start=906829><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=907240><P Class=KRCC>
하나로 통일된 온도 체계가<br>
존재하지 않았던 것이다
<SYNC Start=911143><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=912746><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>장하석 - 런던 대학</font><br>
온도에 숫자를 매기는 방식은<br>
얼마든지 많이 있을 수 있죠
<SYNC Start=918411><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=918639><P Class=KRCC>
그래서 저마다 완전히<br>
중구난방이었습니다
<SYNC Start=922222><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=922587><P Class=KRCC>
피렌체에 있는 누군가는<br>
이런 식의 온도계를,
<SYNC Start=927282><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=927419><P Class=KRCC>
또 런던의 누군가는<br>
다른 식의 온도계를..
<SYNC Start=930886><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=931400><P Class=KRCC>
온도의 척도조차<br>
통일되지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=933939><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=934064><P Class=KRCC>
그래서 온도계를 표준화하는데<br>
많은 어려움이 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=939543><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=940976><P Class=KRCC>
온도 체계를 정한다고 해 봅시다.<br>
어떻게 하면 될까요?
<SYNC Start=944052><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=944236><P Class=KRCC>
17~18세기 온도계 제작자나<br>
실험가들도 잘 알고 있었던 것인데,
<SYNC Start=947863><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=947991><P Class=KRCC>
당연히 해결해야 하는 과제는
<SYNC Start=950232><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=950416><P Class=KRCC>
언제나 일정한 온도를 가지는<br>
어떤 자연 현상을 찾아내어
<SYNC Start=956805><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=956942><P Class=KRCC>
이것을 기준점으로 삼는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=959394><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=959621><P Class=KRCC>
그러한 자연 현상을<br>
'두 개' 찾아낸다면 금상첨화죠
<SYNC Start=964038><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=964255><P Class=KRCC>
좀더 차가운 아래쪽 기준점..
<SYNC Start=968681><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=968943><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 따뜻한 위쪽 기준점..
<SYNC Start=971659><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=971956><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 두 점 사이의<br>
온도를 분할하여
<SYNC Start=975392><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=975470><P Class=KRCC>
쓰기 편하게 100개 정도의<br>
작은 단계로 쪼개는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=978516><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=978786><P Class=KRCC>
문제는, 그러한 현상을 어떻게<br>
찾아내고 정의할 것인가 하는 겁니다
<SYNC Start=985527><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=985996><P Class=KRCC>
아래쪽 기준점으로는 얼음이<br>
녹는 온도를 택할 수도 있겠죠
<SYNC Start=992691><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=994107><P Class=KRCC>
이제 위쪽 기준점으로는<br>
무수히 많은 후보들이 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1000693><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1003867><P Class=KRCC>
아이작 뉴턴은 소위 '열(熱)의 척도'를<br>
정하기 위해 열심히 연구했습니다
<SYNC Start=1010481><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1010739><P Class=KRCC>
그가 정의한 온도점은, 예를 들면
<SYNC Start=1015390><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1015426><P Class=KRCC>
사람이 뜨거운 물에 손을 넣고<br>
겨우 버틸 수 있는 온도..
<SYNC Start=1021689><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1023234><P Class=KRCC>
또는 사람의 겨드랑이 밑 온도..<br>
사람의 혈액의 온도..
<SYNC Start=1028726><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1029060><P Class=KRCC>
양초가 녹는 온도 등이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1032222><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1035669><P Class=KRCC>
널리 사용된 최초의 온도 체계는<br>
다니엘 파렌하이트가 고안했다
<SYNC Start=1040366><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1040476><P Class=KRCC>
그는 네덜란드에서 의료용 온도계를<br>
만든 숙련된 기구 제작자였다
<SYNC Start=1044718><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1046128><P Class=KRCC>
그는 얼음, 물, 소금의 혼합물을 써서<br>
기준점 0도를 잡고,
<SYNC Start=1050046><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1050911><P Class=KRCC>
얼음이 녹는 온도는 32도,
<SYNC Start=1053910><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1054084><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 사람의 체온을<br>
위쪽 기준점 96도로 정했다
<SYNC Start=1058473><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1058667><P Class=KRCC>
이는 현재의 화씨 온도값과 거의 같다<br>
<font color=violet>(화씨 온도의 기준은 나중에 재조정되었음)</font>
<SYNC Start=1061518><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1062058><P Class=KRCC>
파렌하이트의 업적 가운데 하나는
<SYNC Start=1065822><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1066022><P Class=KRCC>
수은을 써서 온도계의 크기를<br>
확 줄인 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1071052><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1071447><P Class=KRCC>
이전의 다른 온도계는<br>
알코올이나 공기를 이용했었죠
<SYNC Start=1075858><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1076107><P Class=KRCC>
수은 온도계는 아주 작습니다
<SYNC Start=1079688><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1080010><P Class=KRCC>
만일 온도계를<br>
의료용으로 쓰려고 한다면
<SYNC Start=1083410><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1083490><P Class=KRCC>
환자의 입에 큼지막한 온도계를<br>
물릴 수는 없지 않겠습니까?
<SYNC Start=1087913><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1088412><P Class=KRCC>
이런 작고 편리한 온도계를<br>
보급한 덕분에
<SYNC Start=1091449><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1091609><P Class=KRCC>
파렌하이트의 명성과 영향력이<br>
높아졌다고 생각합니다
<SYNC Start=1096818><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1099056><P Class=KRCC>
스웨덴의 천문학자<br>
안데르스 셀시우스는
<SYNC Start=1101937><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1102070><P Class=KRCC>
온도 눈금을 100개로 분할하는<br>
새로운 체계를 들고 나왔다
<SYNC Start=1106741><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1107286><P Class=KRCC>
셀시우스의 온도 체계는 원래<br>
위아래가 뒤집힌 것이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1112153><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1112536><P Class=KRCC>
다시 말해 물의 끓는점을 0도,<br>
어는점을 100도로 정했습니다
<SYNC Start=1119002><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1119247><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 어는점 아래로 내려갈수록<br>
온도값이 증가하는 식이죠
<SYNC Start=1123367><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1123872><P Class=KRCC>
사실 이것은 온도계의 역사에서<br>
풀리지 않는 작은 수수께끼입니다
<SYNC Start=1131323><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1131349><P Class=KRCC>
도대체 무슨 생각으로<br>
그렇게 눈금을 매긴 것일까요?
<SYNC Start=1135269><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1135538><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 몇년 뒤, 당시<br>
스웨덴 학술원 원장이었던
<SYNC Start=1142326><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1142608><P Class=KRCC>
식물학자 린네가 나와서,<br>
이런 말도 안되는 방식은 그만두자고
<SYNC Start=1146372><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1146547><P Class=KRCC>
눈금을 뒤집어서 오늘날과 같은<br>
섭씨 온도 체계를 확정했습니다
<SYNC Start=1152169><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1157240><P Class=KRCC>
온도 체계가 만들어질 때만 해도<br>
누구도 생각지 못했던 질문 하나는
<SYNC Start=1161583><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1161709><P Class=KRCC>
"온도는 얼마까지 내려갈 수 있는가?<br>
온도의 절대 하한은 있는가?" 이다
<SYNC Start=1167183><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1168532><P Class=KRCC>
절대 하한이 있을지도 모른다는 발상은<br>
냉기의 역사에 전환점이 되었다
<SYNC Start=1173519><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1177453><P Class=KRCC>
그 시초는 프랑스 물리학자<br>
기욤 아몽통이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1181397><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1181876><P Class=KRCC>
그는 공기를 가열하고 냉각시키면서<br>
팽창과 수축을 실험하던 중이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1189350><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1190118><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>이제 공기 관 주위에 얼음을 놓고<br>
지켜보겠습니다..</font>
<SYNC Start=1193809><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1193937><P Class=KRCC>
그는 공기를 냉각시키면 그 압력이나<br>
부피가 줄어든다는 사실에 주목하고
<SYNC Start=1201469><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1201742><P Class=KRCC>
계속해서 온도를 낮추면 어떻게 될까<br>
추측해 보았습니다
<SYNC Start=1206752><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1207822><P Class=KRCC>
온도와 압력의 그래프를 그려
<SYNC Start=1210440><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1210552><P Class=KRCC>
온도가 낮아지면<br>
압력도 낮아짐을 알아냈고
<SYNC Start=1214710><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1214986><P Class=KRCC>
이것으로부터 그는<br>
놀라운 착상을 떠올렸다
<SYNC Start=1217859><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1218328><P Class=KRCC>
아몽통은 이런 가능성을 고려했습니다
<SYNC Start=1221001><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1221247><P Class=KRCC>
이 선을 연장해서 압력이 0이 되는<br>
지점까지 간다면 어떻게 될까?
<SYNC Start=1225954><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1226191><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 바로, 역사상 처음으로
<SYNC Start=1230297><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1230461><P Class=KRCC>
절대 온도 0도의 개념을<br>
생각해 낸 사건이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1235193><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1235481><P Class=KRCC>
압력 0, 온도 0인 지점이죠
<SYNC Start=1238623><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1238820><P Class=KRCC>
가만 생각해 보면<br>
대단히 혁신적인 발상입니다
<SYNC Start=1242139><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1242324><P Class=KRCC>
왜냐면, 더 내려갈수 없는 온도의 하한이<br>
있다는 생각을 하기는 쉽지 않습니다
<SYNC Start=1249851><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1250082><P Class=KRCC>
위쪽으로는 얼마든지 더 뜨거워질수 있고<br>
온도의 한계가 없으니까요
<SYNC Start=1257295><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1257567><P Class=KRCC>
어쨌든 만약 이런 바닥점 0도가 있다면
<SYNC Start=1262752><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1263123><P Class=KRCC>
이 0도가 얼마나 낮은 온도인지<br>
계산에 의해서 추정할 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1270436><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1270850><P Class=KRCC>
그 계산은 아몽통 자신이 아니라<br>
나중에 다른 사람들이 했죠
<SYNC Start=1275415><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1275987><P Class=KRCC>
그 계산값은 오늘날 알고 있는 수치인
<SYNC Start=1279628><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1279692><P Class=KRCC>
섭씨 약 -273도에서<br>
크게 벗어나지 않았습니다
<SYNC Start=1284532><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1287854><P Class=KRCC>
아몽통은 온도의 상한은 없지만
<SYNC Start=1291257><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1291400><P Class=KRCC>
아래쪽으로는 절대 한계점이 있음을<br>
즉시 알아차렸다
<SYNC Start=1297490><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1297845><P Class=KRCC>
그에게 이것은 이론적 한계점이었을뿐<br>
실제로 시도할만한 목표는 아니었다
<SYNC Start=1302465><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1305077><P Class=KRCC>
지구에서 가장 추운 곳보다도<br>
훨씬 낮은 온도인
<SYNC Start=1308550><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1308684><P Class=KRCC>
이 절대 영도를 향한 모험에 앞서서
<SYNC Start=1311003><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1311239><P Class=KRCC>
반드시 해결해야 하는<br>
근본적인 질문이 있었다
<SYNC Start=1314590><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1317158><P Class=KRCC>
이때의 과학자 대부분은, 냉기의 정체가<br>
열(熱)의 부재라는 것을 알고 있었다
<SYNC Start=1323395><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1323674><P Class=KRCC>
그러나, 물질이 가열되거나 냉각될 때<br>
어떤 일이 벌어지는지는 의견이 분분했다
<SYNC Start=1330258><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1331162><P Class=KRCC>
아몽통 같은 이들은<br>
열이 운동의 한 형태이며
<SYNC Start=1336934><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1337061><P Class=KRCC>
물질을 냉각시키면 입자들이 점점 더<br>
가까워지는 것이라고 굳게 믿었습니다
<SYNC Start=1345350><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1347125><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 안타깝게도 냉기의 과학은<br>
이내 커다란 후퇴를 겪게 된다
<SYNC Start=1351865><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1352191><P Class=KRCC>
입자들의 움직임이 느려지는 현상이<br>
곧 냉각이라는 이론이 밀려나게 된 것이다
<SYNC Start=1357858><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1360196><P Class=KRCC>
열과 냉기에 관한 새로운 경쟁 이론이<br>
18세기 말에 등장했는데
<SYNC Start=1364352><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1364431><P Class=KRCC>
매우 그럴듯해 보이지만<br>
완전히 틀린 이론이었기 때문이다
<SYNC Start=1368441><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1369863><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 '칼로릭 이론'으로,
<SYNC Start=1371964><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1372039><P Class=KRCC>
프랑스의 위대한 화학자<br>
앙투안 라부아지에가 적극 주장했다
<SYNC Start=1376550><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1381865><P Class=KRCC>
당대 대부분의 과학자들처럼, 그는<br>
사비로 연구를 할만큼 부유한 귀족이었다
<SYNC Start=1387355><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1387703><P Class=KRCC>
라부아지에의 부인은<br>
실험 조수 역할을 맡기도 했는데
<SYNC Start=1392348><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1392537><P Class=KRCC>
이들 부부는 유명한 화가 다비드에게<br>
초상화를 부탁할 정도였다
<SYNC Start=1397023><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1399921><P Class=KRCC>
라부아지에는 질량이 없는<br>
'칼로릭'이라는 유체(流體)가
<SYNC Start=1403846><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1403943><P Class=KRCC>
열의 실체라는, 이 잘못된 이론을<br>
입증하기 위해 실험을 했다
<SYNC Start=1409851><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1410814><P Class=KRCC>
그는 고체의 경우 분자들이<br>
빽빽하게 모여 있다고 생각했습니다
<SYNC Start=1416999><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1417191><P Class=KRCC>
여기에 칼로릭을 주입하면
<SYNC Start=1420394><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1420723><P Class=KRCC>
칼로릭이 분자들 사이에 스며들어<br>
결합을 헐겁게 한다는 것이죠
<SYNC Start=1426578><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1427823><P Class=KRCC>
칼로릭은 이처럼 '스스로 반발하는'<br>
속성을 가진 유체라는 개념이었습니다
<SYNC Start=1434385><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1434743><P Class=KRCC>
입자들을 이리저리 흐트러뜨리는<br>
성질을 가지고 있다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1438838><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1439267><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 그가 생각한<br>
열의 기본 개념입니다
<SYNC Start=1442695><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1442860><P Class=KRCC>
즉, 냉기는 칼로릭의 부재 또는<br>
칼로릭의 상대적 부족이라고 본 것이죠
<SYNC Start=1448333><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1451597><P Class=KRCC>
라부아지에는 칼로릭의 양을 재는<br>
칼로리미터라는 기구까지 만들었다
<SYNC Start=1456790><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1457249><P Class=KRCC>
바깥 용기를 얼음으로 채우고
<SYNC Start=1459839><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1460119><P Class=KRCC>
안쪽에는 열원을 넣었다
<SYNC Start=1463684><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1463759><P Class=KRCC>
열원은 화학 반응이거나<br>
또는 동물일 때도 있었는데
<SYNC Start=1467872><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1467924><P Class=KRCC>
여기에서 방출되는<br>
칼로릭의 양을 측정하려 했다
<SYNC Start=1471742><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1473506><P Class=KRCC>
얼음이 녹아 나온 물을 모아<br>
그 무게를 달아서
<SYNC Start=1476703><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1476790><P Class=KRCC>
열원으로부터 나온<br>
칼로릭의 양을 계산했다
<SYNC Start=1480674><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1482279><P Class=KRCC>
매우 인상적인 것은<br>
라부아지에가
<SYNC Start=1485321><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1485392><P Class=KRCC>
칼로릭을 보통의 물질과 다름없는<br>
하나의 물질로 취급했다는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1491612><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1491681><P Class=KRCC>
그가 정리한 물질 원소들의 목록에<br>
칼로릭을 포함시켰을 정도이니까요
<SYNC Start=1495902><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1496790><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>로버트 폭스 - 옥스포드 대학</font><br>
열을 유체 물질로 생각하고<br>
그 양을 따지는 것은 쉽습니다
<SYNC Start=1502135><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1502341><P Class=KRCC>
반면에 (아몽통의) 경쟁 이론은<br>
열을 물질 입자의 진동으로 보았는데
<SYNC Start=1507451><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1507636><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 개념적으로<br>
훨씬 더 어려웠습니다
<SYNC Start=1511509><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1511966><P Class=KRCC>
(칼로릭 이론은) 반증하기가<br>
대단히 어려운 모델이죠
<SYNC Start=1515632><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1515819><P Class=KRCC>
질량도 없는 어떤 물질의 존재를<br>
가정하고 있기 때문입니다
<SYNC Start=1520012><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1520312><P Class=KRCC>
라부아지에에게 칼로릭은<br>
엄연한 원소였습니다
<SYNC Start=1523880><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1524008><P Class=KRCC>
산소, 질소 같은<br>
물질 원소 중 하나라는거죠
<SYNC Start=1527841><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1528166><P Class=KRCC>
그러니까 산소 기체는<br>
산소와 칼로릭이 합쳐진 것이고
<SYNC Start=1532922><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1533182><P Class=KRCC>
여기에서 칼로릭을 제거하면<br>
산소가 액화된다, 이런 식입니다
<SYNC Start=1537083><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1537662><P Class=KRCC>
자유자재로 설명이 가능했기 때문에<br>
이 모델을 반박하기가 참 어려웠습니다
<SYNC Start=1542235><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1542412><P Class=KRCC>
사실, 이 이론만 빼면 라부아지에는<br>
엄청나게 성공한 화학자였죠
<SYNC Start=1547262><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1547678><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 라부아지에의<br>
칼로릭 이론은 곧 무너졌습니다
<SYNC Start=1552363><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1556891><P Class=KRCC>
라부아지에가 틀렸다고 확신하고
<SYNC Start=1560103><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1560218><P Class=KRCC>
칼로릭 이론을 논파하겠다고<br>
나선 사람이 있었는데
<SYNC Start=1563572><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1564826><P Class=KRCC>
그의 이름은 카운트 럼포드이다
<SYNC Start=1567882><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1573301><P Class=KRCC>
카운트 럼포드는<br>
다채로운 이력의 소유자였다
<SYNC Start=1575734><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1575884><P Class=KRCC>
미국 태생인 그는 미국 독립 전쟁 때<br>
영국측 스파이로 활동했고
<SYNC Start=1579792><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1579996><P Class=KRCC>
국외 추방 당한 뒤로는<br>
바이에른 왕국의 정부 요직에 올랐다
<SYNC Start=1585726><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1588247><P Class=KRCC>
그가 맡은 임무들 중 하나는<br>
대포와 관련된 연구였는데,
<SYNC Start=1592047><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1592239><P Class=KRCC>
이 연구를 하던 1790년대에
<SYNC Start=1595547><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1595596><P Class=KRCC>
대포 천공(穿孔) 작업에서 착안해<br>
칼로릭 이론을 반박할 아이디어를 떠올렸다
<SYNC Start=1601181><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1604522><P Class=KRCC>
럼포드는 포신 구멍을 파낼 때<br>
많은 마찰열이 나온다는 점에 주목하고
<SYNC Start=1610903><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1611248><P Class=KRCC>
그 열량을 측정하는<br>
실험을 하기로 마음먹었다
<SYNC Start=1615320><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1616041><P Class=KRCC>
가능한 한 많은 열을<br>
만들어내기 위하여
<SYNC Start=1619238><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1619269><P Class=KRCC>
뭉툭하게 생긴 천공기를 설치하고<br>
그 반대쪽 끝은 물에 담가 두었다
<SYNC Start=1625124><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1626316><P Class=KRCC>
천공기로 포신을 뚫으면<br>
마찰열로 데워진 물은 결국 끓게 된다
<SYNC Start=1633462><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1633808><P Class=KRCC>
천공 작업을 오래 할수록<br>
더 많은 열이 발생했다
<SYNC Start=1637741><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1638671><P Class=KRCC>
그가 얻은 결론은,<br>
열은 운동의 형태이며
<SYNC Start=1643652><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1644049><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 열은 물질이<br>
아니라는 것입니다
<SYNC Start=1647508><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1647542><P Class=KRCC>
포신을 돌리면 돌리는대로<br>
끝없이 열이 발생하기 때문이죠
<SYNC Start=1652710><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1654439><P Class=KRCC>
럼포드의 노력에도 불구하고
<SYNC Start=1656722><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1656883><P Class=KRCC>
칼로릭 이론은 18세기 말까지도<br>
가장 우세한 이론이었다
<SYNC Start=1661674><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1663433><P Class=KRCC>
명성이 드높았던 라부아지에의 이론에<br>
도전하기는 쉽지 않았던 것이다
<SYNC Start=1668107><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1668685><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 그는 불행히도 프랑스 혁명의<br>
소용돌이로부터 자유롭지 못했으며
<SYNC Start=1672852><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1672871><P Class=KRCC>
연구에도 방해를 받았다
<SYNC Start=1675440><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1676462><P Class=KRCC>
그는 공포 정치 와중에 체포되어<br>
결국 단두대의 이슬로 사라졌다
<SYNC Start=1682501><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1684255><P Class=KRCC>
라부아지에가 단두대에 오른 것은<br>
과학적 이유에서가 아니라
<SYNC Start=1687403><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1687430><P Class=KRCC>
프랑스 정부의 국세청 민영화에서<br>
핵심 인물이었기 때문입니다
<SYNC Start=1694165><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1694286><P Class=KRCC>
프랑스에서도 역시나 민영 세금징수원은<br>
가장 미움받는 대상이었던 거죠
<SYNC Start=1701494><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1702374><P Class=KRCC>
라부아지에가 죽은 다음,<br>
그의 아내는 프랑스를 떠나
<SYNC Start=1706613><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1706830><P Class=KRCC>
이윽고 1800년대 초반 서유럽으로 온<br>
럼포드를 만났습니다
<SYNC Start=1712320><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1712596><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 둘은 결혼했죠
<SYNC Start=1714065><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1714236><P Class=KRCC>
럼포드는 자신이 무너뜨린 이론을<br>
만든 남자의 미망인과 결혼한 겁니다
<SYNC Start=1718613><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1720967><P Class=KRCC>
결혼은 오래 가지 않았다
<SYNC Start=1722652><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1722767><P Class=KRCC>
괴로운 나날을 보낸 럼포드는<br>
라부아지에 부인을 떠나
<SYNC Start=1726520><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1726642><P Class=KRCC>
그의 첫사랑이라 할 수 있는<br>
과학에 여생을 바쳤다
<SYNC Start=1731202><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1732233><P Class=KRCC>
열과 냉기에 관한 그의 이론이 마침내<br>
인정되기까지는 거의 50년이 걸렸다
<SYNC Start=1738170><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1740385><P Class=KRCC>
럼포드는 왕립 연구소를 설립하여<br>
과학 연구를 꾸준히 지원했고
<SYNC Start=1746228><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1746502><P Class=KRCC>
냉기의 정복을 향한 다음번 커다란 진전이<br>
바로 이곳에서 이루어졌다
<SYNC Start=1752322><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1756771><P Class=KRCC>
후일 전자기학 연구로 유명해진<br>
마이클 패러데이가
<SYNC Start=1761595><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1761764><P Class=KRCC>
무심코 했던 실험이 절대 영도를 향한<br>
대장정의 시작이 되었다
<SYNC Start=1768026><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1768305><P Class=KRCC>
이제 막 발견된 염소 기체의 성질에<br>
관한 연구가 그에게 맡겨졌다<br>
<font color=violet>(화학자 험프리 데이비의 조수였던 시절)</font>
<SYNC Start=1774038><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1774524><P Class=KRCC>
아마 폭발 위험이 있는 실험이어서<br>
패러데이에게 남겨졌던 것 같다
<SYNC Start=1779819><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1781069><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 같은 이유에서 쉬들로 박사도<br>
이 실험을 재현하고 싶어한다
<SYNC Start=1785662><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1788027><P Class=KRCC>
지금 하려는 실험은<br>
대단히 위험합니다
<SYNC Start=1791346><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1791488><P Class=KRCC>
1823년, 마이클 패러데이는<br>
이 물질을 가열했죠
<SYNC Start=1795922><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1795997><P Class=KRCC>
밀봉한 시험관에 담긴<br>
염소 수화물입니다
<SYNC Start=1799621><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1803069><P Class=KRCC>
- 밀봉됐습니까?<br>
- 네, 됐습니다
<SYNC Start=1804871><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1805026><P Class=KRCC>
아주 훌륭해요
<SYNC Start=1806556><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1808298><P Class=KRCC>
원래의 실험에서, 패러데이는<br>
밀봉된 관을 가지고
<SYNC Start=1811820><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1811876><P Class=KRCC>
결정(結晶)이 들어 있는<br>
한쪽 끝을 가열했다
<SYNC Start=1814781><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1814968><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 반대편 끝은<br>
얼음에 담갔다
<SYNC Start=1817916><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1818373><P Class=KRCC>
그는 곧 노란색 염소 가스가<br>
생겨나는 것을 보았다
<SYNC Start=1822372><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1825058><P Class=KRCC>
기체가 생겨나기 때문에<br>
압력이 올라갑니다
<SYNC Start=1828540><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1829582><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 반대편 끝은<br>
아주 차갑기 때문에
<SYNC Start=1834277><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1834323><P Class=KRCC>
액체 염소 방울이 맺힐 것으로<br>
기대할 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=1839110><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1839195><P Class=KRCC>
압력 때문에<br>
일어나는 현상이죠
<SYNC Start=1841974><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1842964><P Class=KRCC>
지금부터가 위험합니다
<SYNC Start=1845307><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1845674><P Class=KRCC>
이제 몇발짝 뒤로 물러나서..
<SYNC Start=1848478><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1850522><P Class=KRCC>
패러데이의 실험실을 방문한<br>
패리스 박사가 이 실험을 참관했다
<SYNC Start=1855938><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1857358><P Class=KRCC>
패리스는 관 바닥 쪽에<br>
기름기가 있다고 지적했다
<SYNC Start=1860848><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1861790><P Class=KRCC>
패러데이도 호기심이 생겨<br>
관을 깨뜨려 살펴보기로 했다
<SYNC Start=1865337><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1867946><P Class=KRCC>
자, 이 안쪽을 한번 보세요
<SYNC Start=1870721><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1877659><P Class=KRCC>
폭발과 함께 유리 파편이 날렸다
<SYNC Start=1880650><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1880788><P Class=KRCC>
압력이 갑자기 낮아지면서<br>
기름기 있는 액체는 사라졌다
<SYNC Start=1884845><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1889600><P Class=KRCC>
- 지금처럼..<br>
- 이런 일이 있었다는거죠?
<SYNC Start=1891055><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1891131><P Class=KRCC>
네, 정확히 이 현상이었습니다.<br>
펑 터지면서 유리가 날리고..
<SYNC Start=1894758><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1896063><P Class=KRCC>
염소 기체의<br>
강한 냄새가 느껴지죠?
<SYNC Start=1897947><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1898098><P Class=KRCC>
- 네<br>
- 패러데이도 이 냄새를 맡았죠
<SYNC Start=1901691><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1902239><P Class=KRCC>
그는 여기서 강한 의문을<br>
제기했습니다
<SYNC Start=1905906><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1906952><P Class=KRCC>
패러데이는 밀봉된 관 내부의<br>
압력이 증가했기 때문에
<SYNC Start=1911060><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1911181><P Class=KRCC>
기체가 액화된 것임을<br>
곧 알아냈다
<SYNC Start=1913530><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1913801><P Class=KRCC>
그리고는 똑같은 기법을 활용해<br>
암모니아 기체를 액화시켜 보았다
<SYNC Start=1917821><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1918112><P Class=KRCC>
그는 압력이 낮아지면서<br>
액체가 기화할 때
<SYNC Start=1921998><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1922172><P Class=KRCC>
급격하게 온도가 떨어지는<br>
현상에 주목했다
<SYNC Start=1924779><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1925461><P Class=KRCC>
패러데이는 언젠가 이런 냉각 기술이<br>
유용하게 쓰일거라고 예측했다
<SYNC Start=1929443><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1930059><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>암모니아를 이용한<br>
이러한 냉각 기술이</font>
<SYNC Start=1934342><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1934506><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>육류나 야채 등의<br>
식료품을 보관하는데</font>
<SYNC Start=1937219><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1937280><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>효과적으로 이용될 수 있다고<br>
믿을만한 충분한 이유가 있다.</font>
<SYNC Start=1941701><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1943303><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 암모니아를 냉매로 쓴다는<br>
그의 발상은 시대를 앞선 것이었다
<SYNC Start=1948091><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1948419><P Class=KRCC>
뿐만 아니라, 그는<br>
상업적 활용에는 관심이 없었다
<SYNC Start=1952058><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1955741><P Class=KRCC>
한편, 대서양 건너 미국의 한 사업가는<br>
전혀 다른 철학을 갖고 있었다
<SYNC Start=1960499><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1960631><P Class=KRCC>
그는 냉기를 상업화할 계획이었다
<SYNC Start=1963736><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1965093><P Class=KRCC>
프레더릭 튜더는<br>
그의 형과 이야기를 하다가
<SYNC Start=1967900><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1967965><P Class=KRCC>
훗날 미국 최고의 부호가 될<br>
기회를 붙잡았다
<SYNC Start=1971865><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1980127><P Class=KRCC>
저녁 식사 중에<br>
이런 이야기가 나왔던 겁니다
<SYNC Start=1983000><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1983035><P Class=KRCC>
아버지가 물려주신 농장으로<br>
어떻게 돈을 벌 수 있을까..
<SYNC Start=1986170><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1986367><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>데니스 피카르 - 스토로우타운 박물관</font><br>
농장에 바윗덩이들은 넘쳐났지만<br>
누가 그걸 돈 주고 사겠어요
<SYNC Start=1989364><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1989646><P Class=KRCC>
그럼 혹시 얼음은 어떨까, 했던거죠.<br>
얼음을 구하기 힘든 지역도 있었으니까요
<SYNC Start=1993598><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1993796><P Class=KRCC>
터무니없는 생각 같았지만,<br>
결국 대박을 터뜨렸죠
<SYNC Start=1997742><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1999989><P Class=KRCC>
뉴잉글랜드 지방의 호수에서<br>
얼음을 캐내기 시작하면서
<SYNC Start=2003215><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2003456><P Class=KRCC>
그는 많은 수요를 충당하려면<br>
특화된 도구가 필요함을 곧 깨달았다
<SYNC Start=2008306><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2008729><P Class=KRCC>
옛날식 나무톱을 개선한<br>
톱을 사용했습니다
<SYNC Start=2014677><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2014825><P Class=KRCC>
양날이 달린 톱인데
<SYNC Start=2017707><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2017728><P Class=KRCC>
위로나 아래로나<br>
매번 톱질마다 자를 수 있죠
<SYNC Start=2020315><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2023721><P Class=KRCC>
혼자서도 약 12000 제곱미터의 면적을<br>
이틀 정도면 거뜬히 파낼 수 있었죠
<SYNC Start=2027507><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2035942><P Class=KRCC>
어느 곳에나 얼음을 공급하겠다는<br>
튜더의 꿈은 뉴잉글랜드를 벗어나
<SYNC Start=2040764><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2041110><P Class=KRCC>
미국 남부와 캐리비안 등<br>
더운 지방까지 확장하려고 했다
<SYNC Start=2046086><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2047859><P Class=KRCC>
튜더가 상선의 선장들에게<br>
얼음을 선적하도록 설득하니까
<SYNC Start=2053852><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2054195><P Class=KRCC>
물에 떠다니는 배가 왜 물을 싣냐며<br>
모두들 거부했습니다
<SYNC Start=2058254><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2058592><P Class=KRCC>
그래서 직접 배를 사서 쓰려고<br>
자금을 투자 받았죠
<SYNC Start=2063498><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2063609><P Class=KRCC>
그는 배를 사들여<br>
'The Favorite'으로 명명했습니다
<SYNC Start=2065707><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2069946><P Class=KRCC>
뉴잉글랜드 지방은<br>
세계의 냉동고가 되어
<SYNC Start=2072914><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2073051><P Class=KRCC>
캐리비안, 남미 해안, 유럽까지<br>
얼음을 공급했고
<SYNC Start=2077850><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2078181><P Class=KRCC>
심지어 인도와 중국까지 달했다
<SYNC Start=2080892><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2082188><P Class=KRCC>
월든 호수에서 얼음을 캐는 광경을 보며,<br>
헨리 소로<font color=violet>*</font>는 자기가 한때 물놀이를 했던 물이<br>
<font color=violet>* '월든'이라는 책으로 유명한 자연주의 문인</font>
<SYNC Start=2088690><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2088820><P Class=KRCC>
지구를 반 바퀴 돌아 동인도까지<br>
이르는 모습에 경탄을 금치 못했다
<SYNC Start=2094358><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2096809><P Class=KRCC>
튜더는 곧 '얼음왕'이라는<br>
칭호를 얻었으며,
<SYNC Start=2099902><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2100023><P Class=KRCC>
늘어나는 얼음 수요를<br>
충족시키기 위해
<SYNC Start=2103183><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2103272><P Class=KRCC>
말과 대규모 노동력을 동원하여<br>
더욱더 큰 호수들을 캐냈다
<SYNC Start=2107934><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2111111><P Class=KRCC>
19세기 후반이 되자
<SYNC Start=2113238><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2113396><P Class=KRCC>
얼음 산업 종사자는<br>
수만명에 달했다
<SYNC Start=2117672><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2124429><P Class=KRCC>
튜더는 최대의 얼음 공급자이며
<SYNC Start=2128382><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2128426><P Class=KRCC>
미국 최초의 백만장자 가운데<br>
한 명이 되었습니다
<SYNC Start=2131538><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2131768><P Class=KRCC>
캐리비안으로 가는 배 한 척마다<br>
그는 6천달러의 수익을 얻었는데
<SYNC Start=2137244><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2137364><P Class=KRCC>
1년 가계 소득 평균이<br>
2~3백달러였던 시대임을 감안하면
<SYNC Start=2142585><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2142795><P Class=KRCC>
단번에 수천달러를 번다는건<br>
상상을 초월하는 수준이었죠
<SYNC Start=2146088><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2146249><P Class=KRCC>
수송 중에 얼음의 20%가<br>
손실되는데도 이 정도였으니
<SYNC Start=2150008><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2150130><P Class=KRCC>
아무튼 막대한 수익인 겁니다
<SYNC Start=2152209><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2155809><P Class=KRCC>
튜더의 성공을 가능케 한 것은<br>
얼음의 특별한 물리적 성질이었다
<SYNC Start=2160248><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2160408><P Class=KRCC>
얼음을 녹이는데 필요한 열량은
<SYNC Start=2163376><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2163457><P Class=KRCC>
같은 양의 물을 섭씨 약 80도까지<br>
가열하는데 필요한 열량과 같다
<SYNC Start=2168390><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2168676><P Class=KRCC>
따라서 더운 지방으로 보내더라도<br>
얼음이 녹는데는 긴 시간이 걸린다
<SYNC Start=2174311><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2184294><P Class=KRCC>
구멍가게 수준으로 시작했던 일이<br>
전세계적인 사업이 되었다
<SYNC Start=2188338><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2188853><P Class=KRCC>
프레더릭 튜더가<br>
냉기를 산업화시킨 일은
<SYNC Start=2191740><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2191940><P Class=KRCC>
증기기관의 개척자들이<br>
열의 힘을 동력화한 것에 비견된다
<SYNC Start=2195820><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2200139><P Class=KRCC>
1830년대에 이르러<br>
산업 혁명은 절정에 달했다
<SYNC Start=2204413><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2205630><P Class=KRCC>
아이러니하게도, 증기기관이<br>
열을 운동으로 전환하는 원리를
<SYNC Start=2209784><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2209823><P Class=KRCC>
일군의 과학자들이<br>
자세히 밝혀낸 후에야
<SYNC Start=2214690><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2214862><P Class=KRCC>
냉기의 정복을 향한<br>
다음 단계가 열리게 되었다
<SYNC Start=2218262><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2218666><P Class=KRCC>
열기관의 비밀을 푼 다음에야
<SYNC Start=2221508><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2221577><P Class=KRCC>
비로소 냉동 기계를<br>
만들 수 있었던 것이다
<SYNC Start=2226862><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2231695><P Class=KRCC>
"주어진 열량으로부터, 최대한<br>
뽑아낼수 있는 일의 양은 얼마인가?"
<SYNC Start=2236893><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2237351><P Class=KRCC>
이것이야말로, 1800년대 초 유럽 경제의<br>
단연코 가장 중요한 문제가 되었습니다
<SYNC Start=2244781><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2248643><P Class=KRCC>
열의 낭비를 줄이고 높은 효율로<br>
열을 운동으로 전환하여
<SYNC Start=2253442><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2253637><P Class=KRCC>
최대한의 기계적 에너지를 얻어내야<br>
높은 수익을 얻을 수 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=2259001><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2267429><P Class=KRCC>
이 문제에 본격적으로 달려든<br>
최초의 인물은
<SYNC Start=2269811><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2269905><P Class=KRCC>
프랑스의 젊은 포병 기술자<br>
사디 카르노였다
<SYNC Start=2273762><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2274221><P Class=KRCC>
그는 증기기관의 효율을 향상시켜
<SYNC Start=2277527><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2277588><P Class=KRCC>
워털루 전투에서 패배한 프랑스의<br>
휘청거리는 경제를 살리려고 힘썼다
<SYNC Start=2282003><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2282262><P Class=KRCC>
프랑스 국립기술교육원에서 일하면서
<SYNC Start=2285103><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2285187><P Class=KRCC>
그는 증기기관이 열을 운동으로<br>
전환하는 원리를 분석했다
<SYNC Start=2290752><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2293334><P Class=KRCC>
제가 생각하기에<br>
카르노의 독창성의 핵심은
<SYNC Start=2299754><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2299824><P Class=KRCC>
열기관을 이용하여<br>
기계적 에너지를 끌어내려면
<SYNC Start=2306034><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2306097><P Class=KRCC>
높은 온도의 열원,<br>
즉 보일러죠.. 그리고
<SYNC Start=2310442><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2310600><P Class=KRCC>
낮은 온도의 부분,<br>
응축기가 필요하다는 겁니다
<SYNC Start=2314085><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2314326><P Class=KRCC>
카르노에 의하면<br>
열기관의 핵심 요소는
<SYNC Start=2317773><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2317825><P Class=KRCC>
높은 온도의 보일러로부터<br>
낮은 온도의 응축기로 흐르는 열입니다
<SYNC Start=2324334><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2325516><P Class=KRCC>
관찰해보면, 열이 증기기관 내에서<br>
순환하는 것을 알 수 있습니다
<SYNC Start=2331986><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2332102><P Class=KRCC>
열이 이렇게 순환함에 따라<br>
기관은 기계적인 일을 만들어내죠
<SYNC Start=2336213><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2341413><P Class=KRCC>
이것이 의미하는 바는,<br>
열이 소모되거나 사라지지 않고
<SYNC Start=2347278><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2347504><P Class=KRCC>
그저 계속 돌고 돌 뿐인데도<br>
동력이 나온다는 사실이죠
<SYNC Start=2350834><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2350924><P Class=KRCC>
이쯤에서 증기기관의 열을<br>
물레방아의 물에 비유할 수 있겠죠
<SYNC Start=2357654><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2358177><P Class=KRCC>
즉, 증기기관에서는<br>
열의 흐름이 일을 만들어냅니다
<SYNC Start=2363889><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2366239><P Class=KRCC>
카르노는 이러한 열의 흐름을<br>
물레방아에서 물의 흐름에 비유했다
<SYNC Start=2370997><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2373487><P Class=KRCC>
그는 물레방아가 하는 일의 크기가<br>
물의 낙차에 좌우된다는 점에 주목했다
<SYNC Start=2379254><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2382987><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 증기기관도 유사할 것이라는<br>
기발한 아이디어를 내놓았다
<SYNC Start=2386751><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2386879><P Class=KRCC>
뜨거운 부분과 차가운 부분의<br>
온도차가 물의 낙차에 해당된다
<SYNC Start=2392726><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2393471><P Class=KRCC>
온도차가 크면 클수록<br>
더 많은 일이 만들어진다
<SYNC Start=2397172><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2400277><P Class=KRCC>
카르노는 이 아이디어를 다듬어<br>
일반인을 위한 쉬운 책으로 써냈는데,
<SYNC Start=2405254><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2405331><P Class=KRCC>
그때문에 명작으로 평가받기는 커녕<br>
과학자들 사이에서는 거의 외면당했다
<SYNC Start=2411101><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2413039><P Class=KRCC>
이 책입니다.<br>
카르노의 유일한 저작이죠
<SYNC Start=2415742><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2415881><P Class=KRCC>
'열에 의한 동력에 관한 고찰'..<br>
1824년, 118쪽의 작은 책입니다
<SYNC Start=2422021><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2422276><P Class=KRCC>
겨우 600부만 출판되었고, 카르노가<br>
죽기 전까지는 완전히 묻혀 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=2428377><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2428988><P Class=KRCC>
출판된지 20년이 지나서,<br>
스코틀랜드 물리학자 윌리엄 톰슨이
<SYNC Start=2433910><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2434311><P Class=KRCC>
이 책을 구하려고 이곳 파리에서<br>
백방으로 수소문했죠
<SYNC Start=2438600><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2438879><P Class=KRCC>
사료에 따르면, 그는 한참동안<br>
이 책의 행방을 찾으려고
<SYNC Start=2444747><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2444959><P Class=KRCC>
서점을 돌고, 여기 세느 강변의<br>
헌책방 장수들에게 묻고 다녔는데
<SYNC Start=2451216><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2451474><P Class=KRCC>
돌아오는 답은.. 그런 책은<br>
들어본 적도 없다는 말 뿐이었죠
<SYNC Start=2455639><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2460952><P Class=KRCC>
윌리엄 톰슨은 나중에<br>
켈빈 경이라는 칭호를 얻었으며
<SYNC Start=2464661><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2464787><P Class=KRCC>
열역학이라는 이 새로운 분야의<br>
거장이 되었다
<SYNC Start=2468107><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2468291><P Class=KRCC>
그는 열의 순환으로 일이 만들어진다는<br>
카르노의 아이디어에 매료되었다
<SYNC Start=2473913><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2474994><P Class=KRCC>
그런데 파리에서 돌아온 그는
<SYNC Start=2477283><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2477425><P Class=KRCC>
맨체스터의 양조업자 제임스 줄의<br>
또다른 이론에 대해 듣게 된다
<SYNC Start=2482107><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2484217><P Class=KRCC>
줄은 열의 '이동'만으로<br>
일이 생겨난다는
<SYNC Start=2487606><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2487718><P Class=KRCC>
카르노의 아이디어가<br>
잘못됐다고 생각하고
<SYNC Start=2492606><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2492681><P Class=KRCC>
열이 일로 '변환'되는<br>
것이라고 주장했습니다
<SYNC Start=2496157><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2496253><P Class=KRCC>
생각해 보면 이것은<br>
매우 생소한 발상입니다
<SYNC Start=2498938><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2499087><P Class=KRCC>
지금의 우리는 에너지가 여러 형태로<br>
변환된다는 개념에 익숙하지만,
<SYNC Start=2504211><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2504485><P Class=KRCC>
열과 기계적 에너지가<br>
궁극적으로 동일하다는 주장은
<SYNC Start=2510280><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2510424><P Class=KRCC>
당시로서는 혁명적인 것이었죠
<SYNC Start=2513316><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2517525><P Class=KRCC>
그는 자신의 양조장에서 한 실험으로<br>
이러한 이론을 확신하게 되었는데
<SYNC Start=2522340><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2522518><P Class=KRCC>
증기기관과 반대로, 기계적 운동을<br>
열로 변환시키는 실험 장치였다
<SYNC Start=2528274><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2533530><P Class=KRCC>
무게추를 낙하시키고, 그 힘으로<br>
통 안에 든 물을 휘젓는다
<SYNC Start=2538632><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2539143><P Class=KRCC>
이때 일어나는 마찰에 의해<br>
아주 적게나마 열이 발생한다
<SYNC Start=2543559><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2546300><P Class=KRCC>
기계적인 일에 의해 발생하는<br>
이 미미한 온도 증가는
<SYNC Start=2551447><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2551685><P Class=KRCC>
양조업자들이 쓰는 온도계로나<br>
정확히 측정할 수 있었다
<SYNC Start=2555267><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2556245><P Class=KRCC>
줄의 실험은<br>
커다란 의의를 지닙니다
<SYNC Start=2560299><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2560403><P Class=KRCC>
기계적 운동과 열 사이의<br>
변환 비율을
<SYNC Start=2563548><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2563684><P Class=KRCC>
믿을만한 정확도로 측정한<br>
최초의 실험이었기 때문이죠
<SYNC Start=2568329><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2569696><P Class=KRCC>
그는 운동과 열 사이에 뭔가가<br>
변환된다는 것을 확증했고
<SYNC Start=2578656><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2579524><P Class=KRCC>
그 뭔가는 나중에 '에너지'라는<br>
이름을 얻게 됐죠
<SYNC Start=2583005><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2583163><P Class=KRCC>
바로 그 이유로 인해,<br>
국제 단위계의 에너지 단위가
<SYNC Start=2587018><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2587109><P Class=KRCC>
그의 이름을 따서<br>
'줄(joule)'로 명명되었습니다
<SYNC Start=2591589><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2593753><P Class=KRCC>
겉보기에 상충되는<br>
줄과 카르노의 이론은
<SYNC Start=2598777><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2598915><P Class=KRCC>
나중에 톰슨에 의해<br>
'열역학 법칙'으로 통합되었다
<SYNC Start=2603416><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2604086><P Class=KRCC>
줄의 연구로부터 나온<br>
열역학 제 1법칙은
<SYNC Start=2606893><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2606992><P Class=KRCC>
에너지는 다른 형태로<br>
변환될 수 있으나
<SYNC Start=2610138><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2610178><P Class=KRCC>
새로 생겨나거나 사라지지는<br>
않는다는 것이다
<SYNC Start=2614046><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2614727><P Class=KRCC>
카르노의 이론에서 나온<br>
열역학 제 2법칙은
<SYNC Start=2617813><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2617879><P Class=KRCC>
열은 온도가 높은 곳에서<br>
낮은 곳으로만 흐른다는 것이다
<SYNC Start=2622388><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2647438><P Class=KRCC>
19세기 후반에 이르러,<br>
에너지라는 이 새로운 개념은
<SYNC Start=2651203><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2651318><P Class=KRCC>
증기력을 활용한<br>
인공 냉각 장치를 가능하게 했다
<SYNC Start=2655959><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2657322><P Class=KRCC>
현대식 냉장고이든,<br>
증기력을 이용한 얼음 제조기이든,
<SYNC Start=2661818><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2661872><P Class=KRCC>
냉각 기술이 이용되는 곳에서는<br>
고온부에서 저온부로 열이 흐른다
<SYNC Start=2666380><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2672993><P Class=KRCC>
우선, 거대한 피스톤이 암모니아 기체를<br>
압축시켜 뜨거운 액체로 만든다
<SYNC Start=2678762><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2680637><P Class=KRCC>
고온의 암모니아 액체는<br>
펌프에 의해 응축기로 유입되고,
<SYNC Start=2685067><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2685536><P Class=KRCC>
응축기에서 냉각된 다음..
<SYNC Start=2688343><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2689466><P Class=KRCC>
물탱크 아래의 파이프로<br>
흘러들어간다
<SYNC Start=2693061><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2698024><P Class=KRCC>
다음 단계로, 액체 암모니아가<br>
기화하면서 온도가 떨어진다
<SYNC Start=2702961><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2704589><P Class=KRCC>
암모니아가 주변의 물로부터<br>
열을 흡수하면서
<SYNC Start=2707934><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2708067><P Class=KRCC>
물탱크에는 서서히<br>
얼음덩어리들이 만들어진다
<SYNC Start=2712098><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2715034><P Class=KRCC>
1880년대에는 미국 전역에<br>
이같은 얼음 공장들이 생겨나서
<SYNC Start=2719575><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2719690><P Class=KRCC>
하루에 150톤의 얼음을<br>
만들 수 있었다
<SYNC Start=2723308><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2724595><P Class=KRCC>
인공적으로 만들어진 얼음이
<SYNC Start=2728324><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2728395><P Class=KRCC>
처음으로 프레더릭 튜더의<br>
자연빙 산업을 위협했다
<SYNC Start=2732723><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2735810><P Class=KRCC>
미국인들의 얼음 사랑은<br>
그칠 줄 몰랐다
<SYNC Start=2738845><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2739578><P Class=KRCC>
도살장, 양조장, 식품 창고 등등<br>
어디서나 얼음이 애용되었다
<SYNC Start=2744257><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2744509><P Class=KRCC>
시카고의 생산 라인에서<br>
도축된 육류가
<SYNC Start=2747891><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2748033><P Class=KRCC>
냉동차에 실려<br>
철도를 따라 운반되었다
<SYNC Start=2752728><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2753781><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>.. 가축류가 대형 포장 센터를 거쳐<br>
전국의 시장으로 배급됩니다</font>
<SYNC Start=2759165><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2759477><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>갖가지 종류의 식품이 냉동차에 실려<br>
신속, 안전하게 배달됩니다</font>
<SYNC Start=2764155><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2764876><P Class=KRCC>
수천 마일 떨어진 곳에서 생산된<br>
고기로 만든 신선한 스테이크를
<SYNC Start=2769205><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2769257><P Class=KRCC>
미국의 어느 레스토랑에서나<br>
맛볼 수 있게 되었다
<SYNC Start=2773505><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2774432><P Class=KRCC>
과일과 채소를 사시사철<br>
쉽게 구할 수 있게 되면서
<SYNC Start=2779348><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2779475><P Class=KRCC>
도시인들은 최고 수준의<br>
식생활을 누리게 되었다
<SYNC Start=2783168><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2785272><P Class=KRCC>
가정의 식품 보존을 위해
<SYNC Start=2787105><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2787207><P Class=KRCC>
얼음 배달원이 매주<br>
냉장고의 얼음을 갈아 넣었다
<SYNC Start=2791581><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2795602><P Class=KRCC>
냉장고는 사람들의 생활, 특히<br>
식생활에 엄청난 변화를 불러왔습니다
<SYNC Start=2801457><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2801796><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>탐 샤하트먼 - 작가</font><br>
이제 식료품점에 매일이 아니라<br>
매주 한번씩만 가도 됐죠
<SYNC Start=2804674><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2804971><P Class=KRCC>
가게에서는 전세계 어디에서 나온<br>
식품이든지 구할 수 있게 되었고
<SYNC Start=2809101><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2809161><P Class=KRCC>
냉장 수송되어 온 식품은<br>
집에서도 냉장 보관할 수 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=2813242><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2814647><P Class=KRCC>
결국 얼음 배달원은 사라지고,<br>
전기 냉장고가 가정에 보급되었다
<SYNC Start=2820287><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2822838><P Class=KRCC>
전기 냉장고의 기본 원리도<br>
이전의 얼음 제조기와 동일하다
<SYNC Start=2827168><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2827341><P Class=KRCC>
냉매가 기화하며 식품의 열을 빼앗아<br>
뒷편으로 배출시킨다
<SYNC Start=2833389><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2833706><P Class=KRCC>
압축-기화-응축 사이클은<br>
전기식 펌프에 의해 돌아간다
<SYNC Start=2839331><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2840441><P Class=KRCC>
이렇게 해서 냉장고는<br>
윙윙거리게 된 것이다<br>
<font color=violet>(이 문장은 책의 제목이기도 함)</font>
<SYNC Start=2843502><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2845213><P Class=KRCC>
냉장고는 24시간 돌아가기 때문에<br>
전력 회사들에게도 사랑받았습니다
<SYNC Start=2849294><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2849536><P Class=KRCC>
소모 전력량이 크지는 않아도<br>
계속 켜 두는 물건이니까요
<SYNC Start=2853390><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2853737><P Class=KRCC>
지방으로 전력 사업을 확충할 때<br>
홍보 방법 중 하나도
<SYNC Start=2856759><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2856912><P Class=KRCC>
'집에서도 냉장고를 사용할 수 있다'<br>
라는 것이었죠
<SYNC Start=2859585><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2861143><P Class=KRCC>
초창기에는 냉장고의 냉동고가<br>
물을 얼리는데만 사용되었다
<SYNC Start=2865597><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2866088><P Class=KRCC>
음식을 냉동시키면 음식맛이<br>
변해버린다고 생각되었기 때문이다
<SYNC Start=2870051><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2875573><P Class=KRCC>
이 고정관념을 완전히<br>
사라지게 만든 사람은
<SYNC Start=2878225><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2878355><P Class=KRCC>
클레런스 버즈아이라는<br>
과학자 겸 탐험가였다
<SYNC Start=2882824><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2883318><P Class=KRCC>
버즈아이는 1912년<br>
래브라도<font color=violet>*</font>로 탐험을 떠났다<br>
<font color=violet>* 캐나다 동부 끝의 반도 지방</font>
<SYNC Start=2887597><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2889136><P Class=KRCC>
그곳은 영하 40도의 혹한이다
<SYNC Start=2893012><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2902460><P Class=KRCC>
버즈아이는 이누이트족에게<br>
얼음낚시를 배웠다
<SYNC Start=2906402><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2908750><P Class=KRCC>
수십 센티미터 두께의 얼음에<br>
구멍을 뚫은 다음
<SYNC Start=2911131><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2911349><P Class=KRCC>
도구를 이용해서<br>
물고기를 낚아 올립니다
<SYNC Start=2914516><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2914765><P Class=KRCC>
워낙 기온이 낮아서, 잡은 물고기는<br>
둘러메고 가기도 전에 얼어버렸죠
<SYNC Start=2921486><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2923141><P Class=KRCC>
이것을 요리하니까, 방금 잡은<br>
생선처럼 맛이 좋았습니다
<SYNC Start=2926980><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2927223><P Class=KRCC>
이유를 알 수 없었습니다. 집에서<br>
냉동시킨 생선은 맛이 별로인데 말이죠
<SYNC Start=2932854><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2933278><P Class=KRCC>
그래서 그는 집에 돌아와서
<SYNC Start=2935800><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2935922><P Class=KRCC>
급속냉동과 일반냉동에<br>
어떤 차이가 있는지 궁리했습니다
<SYNC Start=2940177><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2945546><P Class=KRCC>
꼼꼼히 조사한 끝에<br>
그는 차이점을 알아냈다
<SYNC Start=2949964><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2952245><P Class=KRCC>
천천히 냉동시킬 경우,<br>
커다란 얼음 결정이 생겨서
<SYNC Start=2956037><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2956110><P Class=KRCC>
생선의 세포 조직을 파괴시킨다
<SYNC Start=2958554><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2958969><P Class=KRCC>
이것을 해동시키면 조직이 파괴되면서<br>
영양분과 향이 씻겨나가는 것이다
<SYNC Start=2964125><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2965975><P Class=KRCC>
'무른 딸기 현상' 이라고도 합니다
<SYNC Start=2967921><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2968127><P Class=KRCC>
싱싱한 딸기를<br>
냉동실에 넣어 얼렸다가
<SYNC Start=2971241><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2971395><P Class=KRCC>
다음날 먹으려고 보면<br>
죄다 물러 터져 있죠
<SYNC Start=2977268><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2977998><P Class=KRCC>
반면, 급속냉동시킬 경우<br>
얼음 결정이 작게 형성되어
<SYNC Start=2982686><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2982787><P Class=KRCC>
세포가 별로 파괴되지 않는다
<SYNC Start=2985077><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2985525><P Class=KRCC>
결국 냉동 속도에 달린 것이다
<SYNC Start=2988385><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2990394><P Class=KRCC>
버즈아이는 이렇게<br>
급속하게 냉동시킬 수 있다면
<SYNC Start=2996127><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2996468><P Class=KRCC>
얼음 결정에 의한<br>
조직 손상이 줄어들어서
<SYNC Start=3001391><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3001517><P Class=KRCC>
다시 녹여 요리를 해도<br>
신선한 재료처럼 맛있다는걸 알아냈죠
<SYNC Start=3005783><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3008110><P Class=KRCC>
원리상으로는 간단했지만,<br>
래브라도에서 경험한 자연적인 과정을
<SYNC Start=3012936><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3013020><P Class=KRCC>
상업용 급속냉동 기술로 완벽하게<br>
재현하는데는 10년이 걸렸다
<SYNC Start=3019759><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3021657><P Class=KRCC>
1924년, 버즈아이는 매사추세츠주<br>
글로스터에서 급속냉동 사업을 시작했다
<SYNC Start=3026274><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3026383><P Class=KRCC>
갓 잡은 생선을 영하 45도까지<br>
냉동시키는 창고이다
<SYNC Start=3030403><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3033283><P Class=KRCC>
그는 이것을 육류, 채소류 등<br>
다른 식료품까지 확장하여
<SYNC Start=3037598><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3037829><P Class=KRCC>
냉동식품 사업을 사실상<br>
혼자 힘으로 개척했습니다
<SYNC Start=3041884><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3043297><P Class=KRCC>
냉동/냉장고는 마침내<br>
현대 생활의 상징이 되어갔다
<SYNC Start=3047144><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3047654><P Class=KRCC>
때를 같이 하여,<br>
또다른 형태의 냉각 기술이
<SYNC Start=3051746><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3052020><P Class=KRCC>
도시 생활 문화에<br>
막대한 영향을 끼쳤다
<SYNC Start=3055593><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3056543><P Class=KRCC>
공기 자체를 냉각시키는 기술이다
<SYNC Start=3059256><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3060822><P Class=KRCC>
드레블이 제임스 왕을 떨게 만들었던<br>
사건으로부터 3세기가 지났다
<SYNC Start=3066476><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3066767><P Class=KRCC>
20세기 초엽, 냉방 기술은<br>
이제 전세계를 뒤흔들 참이었다
<SYNC Start=3072438><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3073584><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>이봐, 그 에어컨인가 뭔가 하는게<br>
대체 어떤 거지?</font>
<SYNC Start=3076897><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3077095><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>자넨 왜 난처하게<br>
그런 걸 물어보나?</font>
<SYNC Start=3079547><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3084476><P Class=KRCC>
미국인의 생활을 바꾼 냉방 기술의<br>
주역은 윌리스 캐리어이다
<SYNC Start=3090761><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3090922><P Class=KRCC>
그의 기술 혁신이 편안한 냉방 기술의<br>
신화를 만들어냈다
<SYNC Start=3095488><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3097687><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>안개 낀 어느날 밤,</font>
<SYNC Start=3099383><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3099482><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>젊은 기술자 윌리스 캐리어는<br>
어떤 문제에 대해 생각중이었습니다</font>
<SYNC Start=3103619><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3103996><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>산업 생산에 영향을 주는 습도를<br>
어떻게 제어할 수 있을까..</font>
<SYNC Start=3108343><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3108600><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>어쩌면 안개에 답이 있을지 모른다</font>
<SYNC Start=3111454><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3112120><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>생각해 보면..</font>
<SYNC Start=3113277><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3113536><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>안개는 수증기가 응축된 것이다</font>
<SYNC Start=3115770><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3116145><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>안개가 만들어지는 것은,<br>
공기가 차가워졌고</font>
<SYNC Start=3118793><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3118826><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>찬 공기에도 같은 양의 수증기가<br>
들어있기 때문이다</font>
<SYNC Start=3122181><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3122533><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>그럼 마찬가지로,<br>
공기를 냉각시켜서</font>
<SYNC Start=3124920><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3125059><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>습기를 응축시키면<br>
습도를 낮출 수 있지 않을까?</font>
<SYNC Start=3130336><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3131244><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>온도를 조절하여 습도를 조절한다,</font>
<SYNC Start=3134231><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3134397><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>이것이 윌리스 캐리어의<br>
아이디어였습니다</font>
<SYNC Start=3137475><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3140047><P Class=KRCC>
1902년, 캐리어는 특별한 임무를 띠고<br>
브루클린으로 파견되었습니다
<SYNC Start=3145182><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3145996><P Class=KRCC>
당시 미국에서 가장 인기 있던<br>
올컬러 잡지 'Judge'의 출판사로 갔죠
<SYNC Start=3150348><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3150535><P Class=KRCC>
그 회사에 아주 큰 문제가<br>
발생했습니다
<SYNC Start=3158350><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3158759><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>마샤 애커먼 - 작가</font><br>
브루클린의 7월 여름 날씨에
<SYNC Start=3163080><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3163176><P Class=KRCC>
잡지 표지에 인쇄할 잉크가<br>
자꾸 미끄러져 나갔던 겁니다
<SYNC Start=3167138><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3167352><P Class=KRCC>
습도가 너무 높았기 때문이죠
<SYNC Start=3170721><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3173704><P Class=KRCC>
선풍기 회사의 신입사원 캐리어는<br>
그가 개발중이던 기술을 응용하여
<SYNC Start=3179876><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3180057><P Class=KRCC>
Judge 1902년 7월호를<br>
인쇄해 낼 방도를 찾아냈습니다
<SYNC Start=3185713><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3185897><P Class=KRCC>
그 길을 시작으로 드디어 자신의<br>
에어컨 왕국을 건설하기 시작했죠
<SYNC Start=3190611><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3194093><P Class=KRCC>
에어컨 수요는 점차 늘어났다
<SYNC Start=3197326><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3197796><P Class=KRCC>
1920년대에는 영화관이 에어컨의<br>
홍보대사 역할을 했다
<SYNC Start=3202341><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3202975><P Class=KRCC>
여름엔 사람들이 더위를 피하려고<br>
영화관에 몰려들었다
<SYNC Start=3206489><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3206878><P Class=KRCC>
극장은 굉장히 인기있었고
<SYNC Start=3208964><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3209087><P Class=KRCC>
에어컨도 관객을 모으는데<br>
분명히 한 몫 했습니다
<SYNC Start=3212286><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3212353><P Class=KRCC>
특히나 푹푹 찌는 날엔<br>
극장에 콕 박혀서
<SYNC Start=3215588><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3215661><P Class=KRCC>
즐거운 시간을 보낼 수 있었죠
<SYNC Start=3218292><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3222952><P Class=KRCC>
에어컨은 일터에서도<br>
점차 일반화되었다
<SYNC Start=3226519><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3226876><P Class=KRCC>
특히 섬유, 담배 공장이 많은<br>
남부 지방에서
<SYNC Start=3230519><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3230589><P Class=KRCC>
냉방은 필수 요건이 되었다
<SYNC Start=3233647><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3234991><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>근로자가 쾌적한 환경에서<br>
좋은 공기를 마실 때</font>
<SYNC Start=3238017><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3238186><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>작업의 품질과 속도도 높아집니다</font>
<SYNC Start=3240635><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3241021><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=cyan>레이먼드 아르세놀 - 남플로리다 대학</font><br>
노동자들을 위해<br>
시원한 근로 조건을 제공하다니
<SYNC Start=3245348><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3245409><P Class=KRCC>
훈훈한 사장님이로구나 싶겠지만<br>
택도 없는 소리죠
<SYNC Start=3249619><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3249886><P Class=KRCC>
의도하지 않은 효과였을 뿐이고,<br>
실제로는..
<SYNC Start=3255027><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3255091><P Class=KRCC>
섬유가 손상되지 않게 하려는<br>
방적 공장의 품질관리법일 뿐입니다
<SYNC Start=3260195><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3260335><P Class=KRCC>
다른 공장에서도<br>
사정은 마찬가지죠
<SYNC Start=3265428><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3265541><P Class=KRCC>
담배 재건조 공장에서는 항상<br>
먼지가 골칫거리였습니다
<SYNC Start=3271697><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3272393><P Class=KRCC>
그리고 제 생각엔<br>
노동자들이 집에 돌아가면
<SYNC Start=3276563><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3276674><P Class=KRCC>
냉방 안되는 방에 앉아서
<SYNC Start=3280235><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3280798><P Class=KRCC>
낮에 시원한 일터에서 보낸 시간이<br>
더 좋았지, 했을겁니다
<SYNC Start=3285318><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3285908><P Class=KRCC>
이 지방에서 오래 산 사람들도<br>
누구나 그렇겠지만
<SYNC Start=3288668><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3288782><P Class=KRCC>
에어컨 천국인 요즘 같은 세상에도<br>
뙤약볕, 땀, 습도는 여전하죠
<SYNC Start=3294039><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3294166><P Class=KRCC>
참고 견디는 수 밖에요
<SYNC Start=3295799><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3296201><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>큰 돈 안들이고 에어컨을 들여놓으면<br>
더위로 고생할 일이 뭐 있습니까</font>
<SYNC Start=3301092><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3301636><P Class=KRCC>
1950년대에 들어<br>
가정용 에어컨이 보급되었다
<SYNC Start=3304990><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3305123><P Class=KRCC>
쉽게 설치할 수 있는<br>
독립된 실외기가 붙어 있었다
<SYNC Start=3308950><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3309416><P Class=KRCC>
이것은 단순한 가전제품이 아니라<br>
새로운 멋진 생활 양식이었다
<SYNC Start=3314064><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3326387><P Class=KRCC>
에어컨 혁명 이전에<br>
남부 지방 마을의 풍경을 보면
<SYNC Start=3331771><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3332479><P Class=KRCC>
사람들, 가족들이<br>
집 밖에 나와 있었죠
<SYNC Start=3335515><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3335674><P Class=KRCC>
자기집 아니면 이웃집<br>
앞마당에 모여 있었습니다
<SYNC Start=3338937><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3339046><P Class=KRCC>
이웃들끼리 자주 오가는<br>
공동체적 전통이죠
<SYNC Start=3342035><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3346070><P Class=KRCC>
에어컨이 이것을<br>
다 바꿔 놓았습니다
<SYNC Start=3348823><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3349342><P Class=KRCC>
요즘은 주택지를 지나다 보면
<SYNC Start=3351511><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3351574><P Class=KRCC>
사람들의 대화가 아니라<br>
실외기의 윙윙대는 소리가 들리죠
<SYNC Start=3355731><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3360175><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>우리집에 뭐가 생겼게요?</font>
<SYNC Start=3361759><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3363085><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>RCA 에어컨이예요</font>
<SYNC Start=3365547><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3365953><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>여자인 저는요, 어머니께서<br>
제 방을 먼지 없는 청결한 곳으로</font>
<SYNC Start=3368961><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3369014><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=lightgreen>만드시려고 얼마나 애쓰시는지<br>
잘 안답니다</font>
<SYNC Start=3372628><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3380905><P Class=KRCC>
냉기를 다스리게 되면서<br>
도시 생활도 바뀌었다
<SYNC Start=3384313><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3386102><P Class=KRCC>
냉장 기술의 발달에 의해
<SYNC Start=3389150><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3389289><P Class=KRCC>
멀리서 생산된 식품도 먹을수 있게 되면서<br>
도시는 넓게 확장했다
<SYNC Start=3394318><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3399707><P Class=KRCC>
또한 냉방 기술 덕분에<br>
도시는 위로도 확장되었다
<SYNC Start=3403687><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3404469><P Class=KRCC>
20층 이상으로는 강풍 때문에<br>
창문을 여닫을 수 없다
<SYNC Start=3408661><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3409435><P Class=KRCC>
하지만 에어컨의 도움으로<br>
100층짜리 마천루도 가능해졌다
<SYNC Start=3414260><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3419557><P Class=KRCC>
새롭게 출현한 이 기술들은
<SYNC Start=3423713><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3423900><P Class=KRCC>
인간을 냉기의 해악으로부터<br>
막아주는데 그치지 않고
<SYNC Start=3428533><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3428701><P Class=KRCC>
냉기를 생산적이고, 관리 가능하며,<br>
효과적인 자원으로 탈바꿈시켰습니다
<SYNC Start=3434741><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3435119><P Class=KRCC>
한편으로는 증기기관,<br>
다른 한편으로는 냉장고..
<SYNC Start=3439843><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3440165><P Class=KRCC>
19세기의 이 위대한<br>
두 가지 상징물은
<SYNC Start=3444283><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3444470><P Class=KRCC>
전세계 경제와 사회를<br>
완전히 바꾸어 놓았습니다
<SYNC Start=3449177><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3451011><P Class=KRCC>
저는 이 모든 것을<br>
'냉기의 상업화'로 해석합니다
<SYNC Start=3456398><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3456657><P Class=KRCC>
두려움의 대상이던<br>
유해한 냉기를
<SYNC Start=3459975><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3460182><P Class=KRCC>
이윤을 창출하는<br>
자원으로 바꾼 것입니다
<SYNC Start=3463972><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3466726><P Class=KRCC>
지난 두 세기 동안의<br>
폭발적인 인구 성장도
<SYNC Start=3470749><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3470872><P Class=KRCC>
냉기의 정복에 힘입은 바 크다
<SYNC Start=3473463><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3473671><P Class=KRCC>
그러나 이제까지는 단지<br>
극저온을 향한 여정의 시작이었다
<SYNC Start=3478033><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3478740><P Class=KRCC>
보다 낮은 온도를 얻는 것은<br>
훨씬 더 어렵지만
<SYNC Start=3483266><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3483355><P Class=KRCC>
미래의 놀라운 기술 혁신을<br>
가져다 줄 것이다
<SYNC Start=3486908><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3488899><P Class=KRCC>
결승 테이프를 끊기 위해<br>
과학자들이 경쟁하면서
<SYNC Start=3492144><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3492290><P Class=KRCC>
그들의 발은 바빠지고,<br>
분자의 요동은 느려진다
<SYNC Start=3496420><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3496617><P Class=KRCC>
마지막 결승선에서<br>
그들을 기다리는 성배는
<SYNC Start=3499645><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3499791><P Class=KRCC>
절대 영도이다
<SYNC Start=3502160><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3503000><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=orange>- 2부로 이어집니다 -</font>
<SYNC Start=3506000><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3507000><P Class=KRCC>
<font color=orange>딕테이션, 한/영 자막 제작<br>
DCinside 과학갤/다큐갤 '디핑'<br>
croydon.egloos.com</font>
<SYNC Start=3512000><P Class=KRCC>&nbsp;

<SYNC Start=4170><P Class=ENCC>
The greatest triumph of civilization is often seen as our mastery of heat.
<SYNC Start=10103><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=12674><P Class=ENCC>
Yet our conquest of cold is an equally epic journey
<SYNC Start=16382><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=16559><P Class=ENCC>
from dark beginnings to an ultracool frontier.
<SYNC Start=20723><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=22086><P Class=ENCC>
For centuries, cold remained a perplexing mystery.
<SYNC Start=25691><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=25872><P Class=ENCC>
Nobody had any idea what it was,
<SYNC Start=28221><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=28457><P Class=ENCC>
much less how to harness its effects.
<SYNC Start=31605><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=32219><P Class=ENCC>
Yet in the last hundred years, cold has transformed the way we live and work.
<SYNC Start=37754><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=38686><P Class=ENCC>
Imagine homes or supermarkets without fridges and frozen foods,
<SYNC Start=42654><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=42918><P Class=ENCC>
or skyscrapers without air conditioning,
<SYNC Start=45197><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=45386><P Class=ENCC>
or hospitals without liquid oxygen.
<SYNC Start=49356><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=51406><P Class=ENCC>
We take for granted the technology of cold,
<SYNC Start=54311><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=54492><P Class=ENCC>
yet it has enabled us to explore outer space and the inner depths of our brain.
<SYNC Start=59667><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=60666><P Class=ENCC>
And as we develop new ultracold technology
<SYNC Start=63674><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=63694><P Class=ENCC>
to create quantum computers and high speed networks,
<SYNC Start=66910><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=67017><P Class=ENCC>
it may even change the way we think and interact.
<SYNC Start=71415><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=73918><P Class=ENCC>
This is the story of how scientists and dreamers over the past four centuries
<SYNC Start=78975><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=79248><P Class=ENCC>
plunged lower and lower down the temperature scale
<SYNC Start=82795><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=82912><P Class=ENCC>
to conquer the cold, enrich our lives
<SYNC Start=85900><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=86043><P Class=ENCC>
and attempt to reach the ultimate limits of cold,
<SYNC Start=89146><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=89421><P Class=ENCC>
a holy grail as elusive as the speed limits of light.
<SYNC Start=93402><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=93650><P Class=ENCC>
Absolute zero.
<SYNC Start=96126><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=109979><P Class=ENCC>
Extreme cold has always held a special place in our imagination.
<SYNC Start=114714><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=114980><P Class=ENCC>
For thousands of years, it seemed like a malevolent force
<SYNC Start=118055><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=118196><P Class=ENCC>
associated with death and darkness.
<SYNC Start=120786><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=121081><P Class=ENCC>
Cold was an unexplained phenomenon.
<SYNC Start=124133><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=126441><P Class=ENCC>
Was it a substance, a process or some special state of being?
<SYNC Start=130967><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=131470><P Class=ENCC>
Back in the 17th century, no one knew.
<SYNC Start=134123><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=134328><P Class=ENCC>
But they certainly felt its effects in the freezing London winters.
<SYNC Start=138493><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=141717><P Class=ENCC>
17th century England was in the middle of what's now called the Little Ice Age.
<SYNC Start=144959><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=145057><P Class=ENCC>
It was fantastically cold by modern standards.
<SYNC Start=147317><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=147415><P Class=ENCC>
You have to imagine a world lit by fire in which most people are cold most of the time.
<SYNC Start=152125><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=152345><P Class=ENCC>
Cold would have felt like a real presence,
<SYNC Start=155601><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=155699><P Class=ENCC>
a kind of positive agent that was affecting how people felt.
<SYNC Start=159735><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=160156><P Class=ENCC>
And that fit it nicely with the most orthodox received view
<SYNC Start=164930><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=165021><P Class=ENCC>
that natural philosophers had inherit from the Greeks, from Aristotle, hundreds of years earlier,
<SYNC Start=170509><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=170847><P Class=ENCC>
that there are two agents in the world,
<SYNC Start=173386><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=173412><P Class=ENCC>
hot and cold,
<SYNC Start=174961><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=175330><P Class=ENCC>
they function symmetrically,
<SYNC Start=177753><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=178030><P Class=ENCC>
they can combine or separate.
<SYNC Start=181026><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=184020><P Class=ENCC>
Back then, people felt at the mercy of cold.
<SYNC Start=187527><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=188248><P Class=ENCC>
This was a time when such natural forces were viewed with awe, as acts of god.
<SYNC Start=193646><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=195995><P Class=ENCC>
So anyone attempting to tamper with cold did so at their peril.
<SYNC Start=201111><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=201953><P Class=ENCC>
The first to try was an alchemist Cornelius Drebbel.
<SYNC Start=206132><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=208452><P Class=ENCC>
On a hot summer's day in 1620, King James I and his entourage
<SYNC Start=212859><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=212918><P Class=ENCC>
arrived to experience an unearthly event.
<SYNC Start=216546><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=218545><P Class=ENCC>
Drebbel, who was also the court magician,
<SYNC Start=221544><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=221590><P Class=ENCC>
had a wager with the king that he could turn summer into winter.
<SYNC Start=226126><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=226468><P Class=ENCC>
He would attempt to chill the air in the largest interior space in the British Isles,
<SYNC Start=231742><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=232308><P Class=ENCC>
the Great Hall of Westminster.
<SYNC Start=234821><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=238690><P Class=ENCC>
Drebbel hoped to shake the king to his core.
<SYNC Start=241908><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=245102><P Class=ENCC>
He had a phenomenally fertile mind. He was an inventor par excellence.
<SYNC Start=249005><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=249350><P Class=ENCC>
His whole world was steeped in a world of alchemy, of perpetual motion machines,
<SYNC Start=254711><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=254732><P Class=ENCC>
of the idea of time, space, planets, Moon, Sun, Gods.
<SYNC Start=258782><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=259042><P Class=ENCC>
He was a fervently religious man.
<SYNC Start=260980><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=261194><P Class=ENCC>
He was a person for whom nature presented a phenomenal.. a galaxy of possibilities.
<SYNC Start=269024><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=271355><P Class=ENCC>
Dr. Andrew Szydlo, a chemist with a lifelong fascination for Drebbel,
<SYNC Start=275424><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=275603><P Class=ENCC>
enjoys his reincarnation as the great court magician.
<SYNC Start=279517><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=281445><P Class=ENCC>
Like most alchemists, Drebbel kept his methods secret.
<SYNC Start=284883><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=285200><P Class=ENCC>
Dr. Szydlo wants to test his ideas on how Drebbel created artificial cold.
<SYNC Start=290656><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=296744><P Class=ENCC>
When Drebbel was trying to achieve the lowest temperature possible
<SYNC Start=299379><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=299488><P Class=ENCC>
he knew that ice, of course, was the freezing point, the coldest you could get normally.
<SYNC Start=304058><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=304276><P Class=ENCC>
But he would have been aware of the facts, through his experience,
<SYNC Start=306545><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=306612><P Class=ENCC>
that mixing ice with different salts could get you a colder temperature.
<SYNC Start=311508><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=312297><P Class=ENCC>
Salts will lower the temperature at which ice melts.
<SYNC Start=316141><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=316497><P Class=ENCC>
Dr. Szydlo thinks Drebbel probably used common table salt
<SYNC Start=320175><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=320294><P Class=ENCC>
which gives the biggest temperature drop.
<SYNC Start=322654><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=325341><P Class=ENCC>
But salt and ice alone would not be enough to cool down such a large interior.
<SYNC Start=330194><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=330521><P Class=ENCC>
Drebbel was famous for designing elaborate contraptions,
<SYNC Start=334222><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=334402><P Class=ENCC>
a passion shared by Dr. Szydlo, who has an idea for the alchemist's machine.
<SYNC Start=339947><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=342154><P Class=ENCC>
So here, we would've had a fan which would've been turned over,
<SYNC Start=346039><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=346115><P Class=ENCC>
blowing warm air over the cold vessels there.
<SYNC Start=350645><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=350844><P Class=ENCC>
And as the air blows over these cold jars,
<SYNC Start=354541><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=354626><P Class=ENCC>
we would have had in effect the world's first air conditioning unit.
<SYNC Start=360056><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=362702><P Class=ENCC>
But could this really turn summer into winter?
<SYNC Start=366051><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=367537><P Class=ENCC>
The idea is to stir it in as well as possible, in the five seconds that you have to do it.
<SYNC Start=373140><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=374500><P Class=ENCC>
Dr. Szydlo stacks the jars of freezing mixture
<SYNC Start=377536><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=377683><P Class=ENCC>
to create cold corridors for the air to pass through.
<SYNC Start=380959><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=385982><P Class=ENCC>
Now we can feel it's very cold.
<SYNC Start=387591><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=387881><P Class=ENCC>
In fact I could feel cold air actually falling on my hands
<SYNC Start=392135><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=392314><P Class=ENCC>
because cold air of course is denser than warm air
<SYNC Start=395290><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=395370><P Class=ENCC>
and one can feel it quite clearly on the fingers.
<SYNC Start=398351><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=401414><P Class=ENCC>
The vital question, "Would the gust of warm air become cold?"
<SYNC Start=406278><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=412366><P Class=ENCC>
I can feel certainly a blast of cold air hitting me as that second cover was released.
<SYNC Start=418680><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=419097><P Class=ENCC>
Well, temperature.. we're on 14 at the moment.
<SYNC Start=422078><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=422659><P Class=ENCC>
Yes, keep it going. That's definitely the right direction.
<SYNC Start=425489><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=426037><P Class=ENCC>
I think possibly even closer still, we'll..
<SYNC Start=429530><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=435402><P Class=ENCC>
So how would the king have reacted to his encounter with man-made cold?
<SYNC Start=439628><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=440653><P Class=ENCC>
He would have been shocked. He wouldn't have known what was happening.
<SYNC Start=442906><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=443092><P Class=ENCC>
He could have in fact been wondering whether they were some action of God's
<SYNC Start=446282><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=446466><P Class=ENCC>
or some sort of demonological forces which were in action.
<SYNC Start=451080><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=451234><P Class=ENCC>
And he would have left hastily, freezing, as he did so.
<SYNC Start=455540><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=456827><P Class=ENCC>
Had Drebbel written up his great stunt,
<SYNC Start=459302><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=459408><P Class=ENCC>
he might have gone down in history as the inventor of air conditioning.
<SYNC Start=462737><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=462970><P Class=ENCC>
Yet it would be almost three centuries before this idea eventually took off.
<SYNC Start=468021><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=469281><P Class=ENCC>
To advance knowledge and conquer the cold required man with a very different mindset.
<SYNC Start=475309><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=477543><P Class=ENCC>
King James' Lord Chancellor Francis Bacon
<SYNC Start=480224><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=480331><P Class=ENCC>
was the first to apply the scientific method to the study of heat and cold.
<SYNC Start=484738><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=485009><P Class=ENCC>
He believed it was important to conduct experiments and analyze the results
<SYNC Start=489448><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=489627><P Class=ENCC>
rather than rely on the established wisdom of the ancients.
<SYNC Start=493449><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=494612><P Class=ENCC>
For Francis Bacon, heat and cold turned out to be right at the center of his world view.
<SYNC Start=501429><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=501668><P Class=ENCC>
One way of understanding why that's so is think why heat and cold matter to human beings.
<SYNC Start=509238><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=509406><P Class=ENCC>
They really matter in the 17th century for two reasons.
<SYNC Start=512082><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=512276><P Class=ENCC>
One is the weather, and one is disease.
<SYNC Start=515238><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=515860><P Class=ENCC>
There was after all an obvious tension in everyday experience
<SYNC Start=519266><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=519464><P Class=ENCC>
between the healthy effects of warmth and healthy effects of cold.
<SYNC Start=523844><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=524305><P Class=ENCC>
Warmth made you healthy because it stopped you radiating away the vital spirits within you.
<SYNC Start=532320><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=532745><P Class=ENCC>
But cold obviously had crucial effects against death as well.
<SYNC Start=537819><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=538017><P Class=ENCC>
It could preserve things for immensely long times,
<SYNC Start=541296><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=541370><P Class=ENCC>
and maybe it could preserve Francis Bacon's body too.
<SYNC Start=544996><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=548968><P Class=ENCC>
Bacon rarely carried out experiments himself.
<SYNC Start=551924><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=552109><P Class=ENCC>
But his one foray into the preservative effects of the cold had disastrous consequences.
<SYNC Start=557590><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=558582><P Class=ENCC>
He took a freshly killed chicken and stuffed it full of ice and snow
<SYNC Start=562862><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=563052><P Class=ENCC>
to investigate how much longer the chicken meats might stay fresh.
<SYNC Start=567260><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=568979><P Class=ENCC>
He was impressed by the results.
<SYNC Start=570756><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=571093><P Class=ENCC>
The chicken did remain fresh for many days.
<SYNC Start=573925><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=574173><P Class=ENCC>
Unfortunately, during the process of exposing his own body to the cold
<SYNC Start=578298><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=578518><P Class=ENCC>
he caught pneumonia.
<SYNC Start=580470><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=582057><P Class=ENCC>
As Bacon lay dying, it dawned on him that
<SYNC Start=584634><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=584714><P Class=ENCC>
his fascination with the cold was going to cost him his life.
<SYNC Start=589147><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=594500><P Class=ENCC>
The irony, tragedy of that rather sad experiment didn't dissuade his followers
<SYNC Start=600081><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=600277><P Class=ENCC>
from doing more experiments on ice, and snow, and its vital or preservative effects.
<SYNC Start=606971><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=608210><P Class=ENCC>
The men who followed Bacon were really convinced that
<SYNC Start=610905><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=610977><P Class=ENCC>
if we could understand the way in which motion, cold and heat fitted together
<SYNC Start=617011><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=617095><P Class=ENCC>
we could save ourselves from diseases, we could unlock the mysteries of the universe.
<SYNC Start=621289><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=625493><P Class=ENCC>
This fundamental question, "What is cold?"
<SYNC Start=628836><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=628979><P Class=ENCC>
haunted Robert Boyle who was born the year after Bacon died.
<SYNC Start=632989><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=633327><P Class=ENCC>
The son of the Earl of Cork, a wealthy nobleman,
<SYNC Start=635881><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=636080><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle used his fortune to build an extensive laboratory.
<SYNC Start=639947><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=642641><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle is famous for his experiments on the nature of air.
<SYNC Start=645854><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=646049><P Class=ENCC>
But he also became the first master of cold.
<SYNC Start=649267><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=649534><P Class=ENCC>
Believing it to be an important but neglected subject, he carried out hundreds of experiments.
<SYNC Start=655409><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=658400><P Class=ENCC>
He worked through, very systematically, a series of ideas about what cold is.
<SYNC Start=665612><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=665820><P Class=ENCC>
Does it come from the air?
<SYNC Start=668184><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=668535><P Class=ENCC>
Does it come from the absence of light?
<SYNC Start=671663><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=671858><P Class=ENCC>
Is it that there are strange so-called 'frigorific' cold-making particles?
<SYNC Start=679532><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=684260><P Class=ENCC>
The dominant view certainly in Boyle's lifetime,
<SYNC Start=687803><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=688080><P Class=ENCC>
the view that he set out to attack, is that cold is a primordial substance,
<SYNC Start=694049><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=694305><P Class=ENCC>
that when bodies get colder, they're sucking in this primordial cold.
<SYNC Start=700256><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=700533><P Class=ENCC>
and as they get warmer, they expel it.
<SYNC Start=703391><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=704048><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle thought that was wrong, and he did experiments to show that it was wrong.
<SYNC Start=709193><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=715184><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle was curious about the way water expanded when it turned to ice.
<SYNC Start=719429><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=719857><P Class=ENCC>
He wondered whether the increase in volume was accompanied by an increase in weight.
<SYNC Start=725006><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=727574><P Class=ENCC>
They carefully weighted a barrel of water and took it outside in the snow,
<SYNC Start=732030><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=732633><P Class=ENCC>
leaving it to freeze overnight.
<SYNC Start=735116><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=738042><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle reasoned that if once the water turned to ice, the barrel weighed more,
<SYNC Start=742777><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=742975><P Class=ENCC>
then perhaps cold was a substance after all.
<SYNC Start=746902><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=747687><P Class=ENCC>
But when they re-weighed the barrel, they discovered it weighed exactly the same.
<SYNC Start=752270><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=755518><P Class=ENCC>
So what must be happening, Boyle guessed,
<SYNC Start=758255><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=758296><P Class=ENCC>
was that the particles of water were moving further apart,
<SYNC Start=762940><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=763243><P Class=ENCC>
that was the expansion, not some substance flowing into the barrel from outside.
<SYNC Start=769578><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=772640><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle was becoming increasingly convinced that cold was not a substance
<SYNC Start=777043><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=777068><P Class=ENCC>
but something that was happening to the particles,
<SYNC Start=780085><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=780290><P Class=ENCC>
and began to think back to his earlier experiments with his air pump.
<SYNC Start=784078><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=786144><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle's idea was that the air trapped in this glass container is springing, it's elastic.
<SYNC Start=793043><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=793227><P Class=ENCC>
As you try and compress it, it resists.
<SYNC Start=795921><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=796095><P Class=ENCC>
Now this is very closely linked in Boyle's program to the way he studies heat and cold.
<SYNC Start=802917><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=803254><P Class=ENCC>
'cause his idea was that as substances like the air get warmer, they tend to expand.
<SYNC Start=809195><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=809462><P Class=ENCC>
It's as though the little particles, little springs..
<SYNC Start=813336><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=813359><P Class=ENCC>
out of which he had imagined each air particle is made,
<SYNC Start=816129><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=816310><P Class=ENCC>
gradually unwinding, so they take up more space, and they expand.
<SYNC Start=821599><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=822460><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle's conclusion here was that heat is a form of motion of a particular kind,
<SYNC Start=829542><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=830012><P Class=ENCC>
and that as bodies cool down they move less and less.
<SYNC Start=835162><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=837898><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle's longest published book was on the cold,
<SYNC Start=840998><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=841141><P Class=ENCC>
yet he found its study troublesome and full of hardships,
<SYNC Start=844760><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=844933><P Class=ENCC>
declaring that he felt like a physician trying to work in a remote country
<SYNC Start=848985><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=849057><P Class=ENCC>
without the benefit of instruments or medicines.
<SYNC Start=852797><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=855178><P Class=ENCC>
To properly explore this country of the cold,
<SYNC Start=858043><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=858221><P Class=ENCC>
Boyle lamented the lack of a vital tool, an accurate thermometer.
<SYNC Start=863659><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=877558><P Class=ENCC>
It was not until the mid-17th century
<SYNC Start=879814><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=879883><P Class=ENCC>
that glass blowers in Florence began to produce accurately calibrated thermometers.
<SYNC Start=884839><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=885216><P Class=ENCC>
Now it became possible to measure degrees of hot and cold.
<SYNC Start=889261><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=892238><P Class=ENCC>
Because rather than mercury they used alcohol which is much lighter,
<SYNC Start=896111><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=896346><P Class=ENCC>
they made thermometers that were sometimes several meters long,
<SYNC Start=899325><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=899508><P Class=ENCC>
and more often wound into spirals.
<SYNC Start=902095><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=903669><P Class=ENCC>
But there was still one major problem with all thermometers.
<SYNC Start=906829><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=907240><P Class=ENCC>
The lack of a universally agreed temperature scale.
<SYNC Start=911143><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=912746><P Class=ENCC>
There are all kinds of different ways of
<SYNC Start=914586><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=914638><P Class=ENCC>
trying to stick numbers through these degrees of hot and cold and..
<SYNC Start=918411><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=918639><P Class=ENCC>
they, on the whole, didn't agree with each other at all.
<SYNC Start=922222><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=922587><P Class=ENCC>
So, one guy in Florence makes one kind of thermometer,
<SYNC Start=927282><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=927419><P Class=ENCC>
another guy in London makes a different kind, and..
<SYNC Start=930886><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=931400><P Class=ENCC>
they just don't even have the same scale.
<SYNC Start=933939><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=934064><P Class=ENCC>
And so there was a lot of problem in trying to standardize thermometers.
<SYNC Start=939543><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=940976><P Class=ENCC>
Imagine that you want to make a scaled of temperature. What do you do?
<SYNC Start=944052><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=944236><P Class=ENCC>
Well, the obvious thing to do, and this was well understood by
<SYNC Start=946817><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=946861><P Class=ENCC>
instrument makers and experimenters in the 17th and 18th century,
<SYNC Start=950232><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=950416><P Class=ENCC>
is to try and find something in nature which you know always has the same temperature,
<SYNC Start=956805><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=956942><P Class=ENCC>
and make that your fixed point.
<SYNC Start=959394><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=959621><P Class=ENCC>
A better strategy even is to find 'two' such phenomena in nature.
<SYNC Start=964038><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=964255><P Class=ENCC>
And then you have a lower fixed point, like something rather cold..
<SYNC Start=968681><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=968943><P Class=ENCC>
and an upper fixed point, something rather warm..
<SYNC Start=971659><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=971956><P Class=ENCC>
and divide the degrees of temperature between
<SYNC Start=975392><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=975470><P Class=ENCC>
and decide 100 convenient bite-size chunks.
<SYNC Start=978516><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=978786><P Class=ENCC>
The problem however was to find, define, a phenomenon
<SYNC Start=982996><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=983038><P Class=ENCC>
whose temperature you guessed was fixed.
<SYNC Start=985527><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=985996><P Class=ENCC>
So for the lower fixed point, you might choose
<SYNC Start=989169><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=989290><P Class=ENCC>
the temperature of ice, just as it's melting.
<SYNC Start=992691><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=994107><P Class=ENCC>
And then there's an almost indefinite range of possible candidates
<SYNC Start=998358><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=998547><P Class=ENCC>
for your upper fixed point.
<SYNC Start=1000693><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1003867><P Class=ENCC>
Isaac Newton, for example, worked rather hard
<SYNC Start=1007243><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1007390><P Class=ENCC>
on constructing what he called 'the scale of heat'.
<SYNC Start=1010481><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1010739><P Class=ENCC>
He for example defined the temperature
<SYNC Start=1015390><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1015426><P Class=ENCC>
which human can only just tolerate if they plunge their hand into warm water.
<SYNC Start=1021689><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1023234><P Class=ENCC>
It could be the normal human underarm, the temperature of the human blood,
<SYNC Start=1028726><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1029060><P Class=ENCC>
the temperature of wax just as it's melting.
<SYNC Start=1032222><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1035669><P Class=ENCC>
The first temperature scale to be widely adopted was devised by Daniel Fahrenheit,
<SYNC Start=1040366><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1040476><P Class=ENCC>
an accomplished instrument maker who made thermometers for doctors in Holland.
<SYNC Start=1044718><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1046128><P Class=ENCC>
He used a mixture of ice, water, and salt for his zero degrees.
<SYNC Start=1050046><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1050911><P Class=ENCC>
Ice melting in water at 32 degrees.
<SYNC Start=1053910><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1054084><P Class=ENCC>
And for his upper fixed point, the temperature of the human body at 96 degrees,
<SYNC Start=1058473><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1058667><P Class=ENCC>
which is close to the modern value.
<SYNC Start=1061518><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1062058><P Class=ENCC>
One of the things that Fahrenheit was able to achieve was
<SYNC Start=1065822><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1066022><P Class=ENCC>
to make thermometers quite small, and that he did by using mercury,
<SYNC Start=1071052><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1071447><P Class=ENCC>
as opposed to alcohol or air which other people had used.
<SYNC Start=1075858><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1076107><P Class=ENCC>
And because mercury thermometers are compact,
<SYNC Start=1079688><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1080010><P Class=ENCC>
clearly if you're trying to use it for clinical purposes,
<SYNC Start=1083410><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1083490><P Class=ENCC>
you don't want some big thing sticking out of the patient, so..
<SYNC Start=1087913><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1088412><P Class=ENCC>
the fact that he could make them small and convenient,
<SYNC Start=1091449><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1091609><P Class=ENCC>
that seems to be what made Fahrenheit so famous and so influential.
<SYNC Start=1096818><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1099056><P Class=ENCC>
It was a Swedish astronomer Anders Celsius
<SYNC Start=1101937><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1102070><P Class=ENCC>
who came up with the idea of dividing the scale into 100 divisions.
<SYNC Start=1106741><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1107286><P Class=ENCC>
The original scale used by Celsius was upside down.
<SYNC Start=1112153><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1112536><P Class=ENCC>
So he had the boiling point of water as zero, and the freezing point as 100,
<SYNC Start=1119002><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1119247><P Class=ENCC>
with numbers just continuing to increase as we go below freezing.
<SYNC Start=1123367><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1123872><P Class=ENCC>
And this is another little mystery
<SYNC Start=1127376><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1127480><P Class=ENCC>
in the history of the thermometer that we just don't know for sure,
<SYNC Start=1131323><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1131349><P Class=ENCC>
What was he thinking when he labeled it this way?
<SYNC Start=1135269><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1135538><P Class=ENCC>
And it was the botanist Linnaeus, who was then the president of the Swedish Academy who,
<SYNC Start=1142326><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1142608><P Class=ENCC>
after a few years, said, "Well, we need to stop this nonsense!"
<SYNC Start=1146372><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1146547><P Class=ENCC>
and inverted the scale to give us what we now call Celsius scale, today.
<SYNC Start=1152169><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1157240><P Class=ENCC>
A question nobody thought to ask when devising temperature scales was
<SYNC Start=1161583><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1161709><P Class=ENCC>
"How low can you go? Is there an absolute lower limit of temperature?"
<SYNC Start=1167183><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1168532><P Class=ENCC>
The idea that there might be, would become a turning point in the history of cold.
<SYNC Start=1173519><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1177453><P Class=ENCC>
The story begins with the French physicist Guillaume Amontons.
<SYNC Start=1181397><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1181876><P Class=ENCC>
He was doing experiments heating and cooling bodies of air
<SYNC Start=1186724><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1186761><P Class=ENCC>
to see how they expand and contract.
<SYNC Start=1189350><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1190118><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>We're now going to put ice around the air bulb, and see what happens..</font>
<SYNC Start=1193809><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1193937><P Class=ENCC>
And he was noticing that, well, when you cool a body of air
<SYNC Start=1198584><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1198620><P Class=ENCC>
the volume or the pressure would go down.
<SYNC Start=1201469><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1201742><P Class=ENCC>
And he speculated, "Well, what would happen if we just kept cooling it?"
<SYNC Start=1206752><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1207822><P Class=ENCC>
By plotting temperature against pressure,
<SYNC Start=1210440><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1210552><P Class=ENCC>
Amontons saw that as the temperature dropped, so did the pressure.
<SYNC Start=1214710><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1214986><P Class=ENCC>
And this gave him an extraordinary idea.
<SYNC Start=1217859><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1218328><P Class=ENCC>
Amontons started to consider the possibility,
<SYNC Start=1221001><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1221247><P Class=ENCC>
"What would happen if you projected this line back until the pressure was zero?"
<SYNC Start=1225954><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1226191><P Class=ENCC>
And this was the first time in the course of history that
<SYNC Start=1230297><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1230461><P Class=ENCC>
people have actually considered the concept of an absolute zero of temperature,
<SYNC Start=1235193><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1235481><P Class=ENCC>
zero pressure, zero temperature.
<SYNC Start=1238623><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1238820><P Class=ENCC>
It was quite a revolutionary idea when you think about it,
<SYNC Start=1242139><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1242324><P Class=ENCC>
because you wouldn't just think that temperature has a limit of lower bound, or zero,
<SYNC Start=1249851><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1250082><P Class=ENCC>
because in the upper end it can go on forever, we think, until it's hotter and hotter and hotter.
<SYNC Start=1257295><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1257567><P Class=ENCC>
But somehow, maybe there's a zero point where this all begins.
<SYNC Start=1262752><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1263123><P Class=ENCC>
So you could actually give a calculation of where this zero point would be.
<SYNC Start=1270436><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1270850><P Class=ENCC>
Amontons didn't do that calculation himself, but some other people did later on.
<SYNC Start=1275415><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1275987><P Class=ENCC>
And when you do it, you get a value that's actually not that far from
<SYNC Start=1279628><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1279692><P Class=ENCC>
the modern value of roughly -273 centigrade.
<SYNC Start=1284532><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1287854><P Class=ENCC>
In one stroke, Amontons had realized that although temperatures might go on rising forever,
<SYNC Start=1293389><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1293535><P Class=ENCC>
they could only fall as far as this absolute point.
<SYNC Start=1297490><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1297845><P Class=ENCC>
For him, this was a theoretical limit, not a goal to attempt to reach.
<SYNC Start=1302465><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1305077><P Class=ENCC>
Before scientists could venture towards this zero point,
<SYNC Start=1308550><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1308684><P Class=ENCC>
far beyond the coldest temperatures on Earth,
<SYNC Start=1311003><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1311239><P Class=ENCC>
they needed to resolve a fundamental question.
<SYNC Start=1314590><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1317158><P Class=ENCC>
By now for most scientists, the penny had dropped.
<SYNC Start=1320049><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1320257><P Class=ENCC>
The cold was simply the absence of heat.
<SYNC Start=1323395><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1323674><P Class=ENCC>
But what was actually happening as substances warmed or cooled was still hotly debated.
<SYNC Start=1330258><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1331162><P Class=ENCC>
The argument of men like Amontons relied completely on the idea
<SYNC Start=1334942><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1335031><P Class=ENCC>
that heat is a form of motion and that particles move more and more closely together
<SYNC Start=1341055><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1341179><P Class=ENCC>
as the substance in which they're in gets cooler and cooler.
<SYNC Start=1345350><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1347125><P Class=ENCC>
Unfortunately, the science of cold was about to suffer a serious setback.
<SYNC Start=1351865><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1352191><P Class=ENCC>
The idea that cooling was caused by particles slowing down began to go out of fashion.
<SYNC Start=1357858><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1360196><P Class=ENCC>
At the end of the 18th century, a rival theory of heat and cold emerged
<SYNC Start=1364352><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1364431><P Class=ENCC>
that was tantalizingly appealing, but completely wrong.
<SYNC Start=1368441><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1369863><P Class=ENCC>
It was called the 'caloric theory',
<SYNC Start=1371964><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1372039><P Class=ENCC>
and its principal advocate was the great French chemist Antoine Lavoisier.
<SYNC Start=1376550><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1381865><P Class=ENCC>
Like most scientists of the time, Lavoisier was a rich aristocrat who funded his own research.
<SYNC Start=1387355><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1387703><P Class=ENCC>
He and his wife, Madame Lavoisier, who assisted with his experiments,
<SYNC Start=1392348><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1392537><P Class=ENCC>
even commissioned the celebrated painter David to paint their portrait.
<SYNC Start=1397023><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1399921><P Class=ENCC>
Lavoisier carried out experiments to support the erroneous idea
<SYNC Start=1403846><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1403943><P Class=ENCC>
that heat was a substance, a weightless fluid, that he called 'caloric'.
<SYNC Start=1409851><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1410814><P Class=ENCC>
He thought, in the solid state of matter, molecules were just packed close in together,
<SYNC Start=1416999><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1417191><P Class=ENCC>
and when you added more and more caloric to this,
<SYNC Start=1420394><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1420723><P Class=ENCC>
the caloric would insinuate itself between these particles of matter and loosen them up.
<SYNC Start=1426578><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1427823><P Class=ENCC>
So the basic notion was that caloric was this fluid that was, as he put it, 'self-repulsive'.
<SYNC Start=1434385><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1434743><P Class=ENCC>
It just tended to break things apart from each other.
<SYNC Start=1438838><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1439267><P Class=ENCC>
And that's his basic notion of heat.
<SYNC Start=1442695><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1442860><P Class=ENCC>
So cold is just the absence of caloric, or the relative lack of caloric.
<SYNC Start=1448333><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1451597><P Class=ENCC>
Lavoisier even had an apparatus to measure caloric, which he called a calorimeter.
<SYNC Start=1456790><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1457249><P Class=ENCC>
He packed the outer compartment with ice.
<SYNC Start=1459839><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1460119><P Class=ENCC>
Inside he conducted experiments that generated heat,
<SYNC Start=1463684><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1463759><P Class=ENCC>
sometimes from chemical reactions, sometimes from animals,
<SYNC Start=1467872><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1467924><P Class=ENCC>
to determine how much caloric was released.
<SYNC Start=1471742><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1473506><P Class=ENCC>
He collected the water from the melting ice and weighed it
<SYNC Start=1476703><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1476790><P Class=ENCC>
to calculate the amount of caloric generated from each source.
<SYNC Start=1480674><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1482279><P Class=ENCC>
I think the most striking thing about Lavoisier is that
<SYNC Start=1485321><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1485392><P Class=ENCC>
he sees caloric as a substance which is exactly comparable with ordinary matter,
<SYNC Start=1491612><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1491681><P Class=ENCC>
to the point that he includes caloric in his list of the elements.
<SYNC Start=1495902><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1496790><P Class=ENCC>
It's very easy to talk about the quantity of heat and to think of it as a fluid,
<SYNC Start=1502135><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1502341><P Class=ENCC>
whereas to talk about the quantity of heat and to think of it as vibration of the particles of matter,
<SYNC Start=1507451><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1507636><P Class=ENCC>
which was the other alternative, that's much more difficult conceptually.
<SYNC Start=1511509><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1511966><P Class=ENCC>
It's a very hard model to refute,
<SYNC Start=1515632><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1515819><P Class=ENCC>
because if you can accept that there is a substance that doesn't have any weight.
<SYNC Start=1520012><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1520312><P Class=ENCC>
Indeed for Lavoisier, heat, caloric, is an element.
<SYNC Start=1523880><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1524008><P Class=ENCC>
It's an element like oxygen or nitrogen.
<SYNC Start=1527841><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1528166><P Class=ENCC>
Oxygen gas is made of oxygen plus caloric.
<SYNC Start=1532922><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1533182><P Class=ENCC>
If you take the caloric away, presumably the oxygen might liquefy.
<SYNC Start=1537083><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1537662><P Class=ENCC>
So it's a very hard model to shift, because it explains so much.
<SYNC Start=1542235><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1542412><P Class=ENCC>
And indeed, Lavoisier's chemistry was so otherwise extraordinarily successful.
<SYNC Start=1547262><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1547678><P Class=ENCC>
However, Lavoisier's story about caloric was soon undermined.
<SYNC Start=1552363><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1556891><P Class=ENCC>
There was one man who was convinced Lavoisier was wrong
<SYNC Start=1560103><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1560218><P Class=ENCC>
and was determined to destroy the caloric theory.
<SYNC Start=1563572><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1564826><P Class=ENCC>
His name was Count Rumford.
<SYNC Start=1567882><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1573301><P Class=ENCC>
Count Rumford had a colorful past.
<SYNC Start=1575734><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1575884><P Class=ENCC>
He was born in America, spied for the British during the Revolution,
<SYNC Start=1579792><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1579996><P Class=ENCC>
and after being forced into exile, became an influential government minister in Bavaria.
<SYNC Start=1585726><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1588247><P Class=ENCC>
Among his varied responsibilities was the artillery works.
<SYNC Start=1592047><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1592239><P Class=ENCC>
And it was here in the 1790's that he began to think about
<SYNC Start=1595547><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1595596><P Class=ENCC>
how he might be able to disprove the caloric theory using cannon boring.
<SYNC Start=1601181><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1604522><P Class=ENCC>
Rumford had noticed that the friction from boring out a cannon barrel generated a lot of heat.
<SYNC Start=1610903><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1611248><P Class=ENCC>
He decided to carry out experiments to measure how much.
<SYNC Start=1615320><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1616041><P Class=ENCC>
He adapted the machine to produce even more heat
<SYNC Start=1619238><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1619269><P Class=ENCC>
by installing a blunt borer that had one end submerged in a jacket of water.
<SYNC Start=1625124><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1626316><P Class=ENCC>
As the cannon turned against the borer,
<SYNC Start=1628973><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1629028><P Class=ENCC>
the temperature of the water increased, and eventually, boiled.
<SYNC Start=1633362><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1633808><P Class=ENCC>
The longer he bored, the more heat was produced.
<SYNC Start=1637741><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1638671><P Class=ENCC>
For Rumford, what this showed was that heat must be a form of motion,
<SYNC Start=1643652><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1644049><P Class=ENCC>
and heat is not a substance because you could generate
<SYNC Start=1647508><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1647542><P Class=ENCC>
indefinitely large amounts of heat simply by turning the cannon.
<SYNC Start=1652710><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1654439><P Class=ENCC>
Despite Count Rumford's best efforts,
<SYNC Start=1656722><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1656883><P Class=ENCC>
Lavoisier's caloric theory remained dominant until the end of the 18th century.
<SYNC Start=1661674><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1663433><P Class=ENCC>
His prestige as a scientist meant that few dared challenge his ideas.
<SYNC Start=1668107><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1668685><P Class=ENCC>
Sadly, this did not protect him from the revolutionary turmoil in France
<SYNC Start=1672852><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1672871><P Class=ENCC>
which was about to interrupt his research.
<SYNC Start=1675440><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1676462><P Class=ENCC>
At the height of the Reign of Terror, Lavoisier was arrested and eventually guillotined.
<SYNC Start=1682501><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1684255><P Class=ENCC>
The reason he was guillotined was not because of his science,
<SYNC Start=1687403><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1687430><P Class=ENCC>
but because he helped to run the privatized income tax service of the French state.
<SYNC Start=1694165><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1694286><P Class=ENCC>
There's nothing more unpopular even in France than a privatized tax collector.
<SYNC Start=1701494><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1702374><P Class=ENCC>
Once he was guillotined, his wife left France and..
<SYNC Start=1706613><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1706830><P Class=ENCC>
eventually met Rumford, when he moved to Western Europe in the early 1800's.
<SYNC Start=1712320><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1712596><P Class=ENCC>
Rumford then married her.
<SYNC Start=1714065><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1714236><P Class=ENCC>
So he'd married the widow of the man who'd founded the theory that he'd destroyed.
<SYNC Start=1718613><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1720967><P Class=ENCC>
The marriage was short-lived.
<SYNC Start=1722652><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1722767><P Class=ENCC>
After a tormented year, Rumford left Madame Lavoisier
<SYNC Start=1726520><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1726642><P Class=ENCC>
and devoted the rest of his life to his first love, science.
<SYNC Start=1731202><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1732233><P Class=ENCC>
It would be nearly 50 years before his theory of heat and cold was finally accepted.
<SYNC Start=1738170><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1740385><P Class=ENCC>
A founder of the Royal Institution, Rumford continued to support the pursuit of science,
<SYNC Start=1746228><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1746502><P Class=ENCC>
and it was here that the next major breakthrough in the conquest of cold would occur.
<SYNC Start=1752322><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1756771><P Class=ENCC>
Michael Faraday, who later became famous for his work on electricity and magnetism,
<SYNC Start=1761595><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1761764><P Class=ENCC>
unwittingly carried out an experiment that would begin the long descent towards absolute zero.
<SYNC Start=1768026><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1768305><P Class=ENCC>
He was asked to explore the properties of newly discovered pungent gas called chlorine.
<SYNC Start=1774038><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1774524><P Class=ENCC>
This experiment was potentially explosive, which is perhaps why it was left to Faraday,
<SYNC Start=1779819><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1781069><P Class=ENCC>
and perhaps also why Dr. Andrew Szydlo is curious to repeat it today.
<SYNC Start=1785662><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1788027><P Class=ENCC>
We are about to undertake an exceedingly dangerous experiment
<SYNC Start=1791346><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1791488><P Class=ENCC>
in which Michael Faraday, in 1823, heated this substance here,
<SYNC Start=1795922><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1795997><P Class=ENCC>
the hydrate of chlorine, in a sealed tube.
<SYNC Start=1799621><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1803069><P Class=ENCC>
- Is that sealed?<br>
- That's sealed, Andrew.
<SYNC Start=1804871><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1805026><P Class=ENCC>
That's absolutely brilliant.
<SYNC Start=1806556><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1808298><P Class=ENCC>
In the original experiment, Faraday took the sealed tube
<SYNC Start=1811820><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1811876><P Class=ENCC>
and heated the end containing the crystals.
<SYNC Start=1814781><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1814968><P Class=ENCC>
He put the other end in an ice bath.
<SYNC Start=1817916><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1818373><P Class=ENCC>
Soon, he noticed yellow chlorine gas being given off.
<SYNC Start=1822372><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1825058><P Class=ENCC>
Because the gas is being produced, pressure's building up.
<SYNC Start=1828540><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1829582><P Class=ENCC>
But because this side is so very cold, hopefully what we'll see is
<SYNC Start=1834277><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1834323><P Class=ENCC>
some tiny oily droplets of liquid chlorine being produced.
<SYNC Start=1839110><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1839195><P Class=ENCC>
It's the pressure which is causing this.
<SYNC Start=1841974><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1842964><P Class=ENCC>
Ray, this is where it starts to get dangerous.
<SYNC Start=1845307><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1845674><P Class=ENCC>
So if you now take a few steps back..
<SYNC Start=1848478><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1850522><P Class=ENCC>
When Faraday did the experiment, a visitor, Dr. Paris, called in to see what he was up to.
<SYNC Start=1855938><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1857358><P Class=ENCC>
Paris pointed out some oily matter in the bottom of the tube.
<SYNC Start=1860848><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1861790><P Class=ENCC>
Faraday was curious, and decided to break open the tube.
<SYNC Start=1865337><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1867946><P Class=ENCC>
Right, so let's have a look inside here.
<SYNC Start=1870721><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1877659><P Class=ENCC>
The explosion sent shards of glass flying.
<SYNC Start=1880650><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1880788><P Class=ENCC>
With the sudden release of pressure, the oily liquid vanished.
<SYNC Start=1884845><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1889600><P Class=ENCC>
- And there we are..<br>
- Is that what happened?
<SYNC Start=1891055><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1891131><P Class=ENCC>
Yeah, that's exactly what happened. It popped open, glass flew..
<SYNC Start=1894758><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1896063><P Class=ENCC>
And can you detect the strong smell of chlorine?
<SYNC Start=1897947><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1898098><P Class=ENCC>
- I can now.<br>
- Absolutely. Well, he detected the strong smell of chlorine.
<SYNC Start=1901691><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1902239><P Class=ENCC>
And this was a major mystery for him.
<SYNC Start=1905906><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1906952><P Class=ENCC>
Faraday soon realized the increased pressure inside the sealed tube
<SYNC Start=1911060><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1911181><P Class=ENCC>
had caused the gas to liquefy.
<SYNC Start=1913530><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1913801><P Class=ENCC>
Later, he used the same technique to liquefy ammonia gas.
<SYNC Start=1917821><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1918112><P Class=ENCC>
He noticed that on releasing the pressure the liquid evaporated,
<SYNC Start=1921998><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1922172><P Class=ENCC>
triggering a dramatic drop in temperature.
<SYNC Start=1924779><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1925461><P Class=ENCC>
He predicted that one day this cooling might be useful.
<SYNC Start=1929443><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1930059><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>There is great reason to believe that this cooling technique with ammonia</font>
<SYNC Start=1934342><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1934506><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>may be successfully employed for the preservation of</font>
<SYNC Start=1937219><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1937280><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>animal and vegetable substances for the purposes of food.</font>
<SYNC Start=1941701><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1943303><P Class=ENCC>
But Faraday's ideas of using ammonia as a refrigerant was ahead of its time.
<SYNC Start=1948091><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1948419><P Class=ENCC>
Besides, he had no interest in commercial exploitation.
<SYNC Start=1952058><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1955741><P Class=ENCC>
Across the Atlantic, a Yankee entrepreneur had a very different philosophy
<SYNC Start=1960499><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1960631><P Class=ENCC>
and was about to commercialize cold.
<SYNC Start=1963736><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1965093><P Class=ENCC>
Frederic Tudor had a chance conversation with his brother
<SYNC Start=1967900><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1967965><P Class=ENCC>
that led him on a path to become one of the richest men in America.
<SYNC Start=1971865><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1980127><P Class=ENCC>
The story goes: at the dinner table, they were trying to decide
<SYNC Start=1983000><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1983035><P Class=ENCC>
what they had on their father's farm they could make money off of, and..
<SYNC Start=1986170><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1986367><P Class=ENCC>
certainly there was a lot of rocks, but people weren't going to pay for that.
<SYNC Start=1989364><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1989646><P Class=ENCC>
So they came up with the idea of maybe ice, because some of the areas did not have ice.
<SYNC Start=1993598><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1993796><P Class=ENCC>
And it seemed kind of crazy at first, but it paid off.
<SYNC Start=1997742><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=1999989><P Class=ENCC>
When Tudor began harvesting ice from New England ponds
<SYNC Start=2003215><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2003456><P Class=ENCC>
he soon realized he needed specialized tools to keep up with the huge demand.
<SYNC Start=2008306><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2008729><P Class=ENCC>
We had the saws, and the saws were an improvement over the old wood saws.
<SYNC Start=2014677><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2014825><P Class=ENCC>
They have teeth that are sharpened on both sides and set,
<SYNC Start=2017707><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2017728><P Class=ENCC>
so it cuts on both the up and the down stroke.
<SYNC Start=2020315><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2023721><P Class=ENCC>
A crew could clear a three-acre pond easily in a couple of days.
<SYNC Start=2027507><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2035942><P Class=ENCC>
Tudor's dream to make ice available to all was not confined to New England.
<SYNC Start=2040764><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2041110><P Class=ENCC>
He wanted to ship ice to hot parts of the world like the Caribbean and the Deep South.
<SYNC Start=2046086><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2047859><P Class=ENCC>
When Tudor first tried to convince shipmasters to put his load of frozen water into the ships,
<SYNC Start=2053852><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2054195><P Class=ENCC>
they all refused because they told him that water belonged outside the hull, not inside.
<SYNC Start=2058254><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2058592><P Class=ENCC>
So he had to go find other investors to get the money to buy his own ship.
<SYNC Start=2063498><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2063609><P Class=ENCC>
And he bought a ship by the name of The Favorite.
<SYNC Start=2065707><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2069946><P Class=ENCC>
New England became the refrigerator for the world
<SYNC Start=2072914><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2073051><P Class=ENCC>
with ice shipments to the Caribbean, the coast of South America and Europe.
<SYNC Start=2077850><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2078181><P Class=ENCC>
Tudor even reached India and China.
<SYNC Start=2080892><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2082188><P Class=ENCC>
Watching the ice cutters working Walden Pond,
<SYNC Start=2084933><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2085064><P Class=ENCC>
Henry Thoreau marveled that water from his bathing beach
<SYNC Start=2088690><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2088820><P Class=ENCC>
was traveling halfway around the globe
<SYNC Start=2090861><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2091095><P Class=ENCC>
to end up in the cup of an East Indian philosopher.
<SYNC Start=2094358><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2096809><P Class=ENCC>
Tudor, who soon became known as the 'Ice King',
<SYNC Start=2099902><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2100023><P Class=ENCC>
began using horses and huge teams of workers
<SYNC Start=2103183><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2103272><P Class=ENCC>
to harvest larger and larger lakes, as the demand for ice grew.
<SYNC Start=2107934><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2111111><P Class=ENCC>
During the latter half of the 19th century,
<SYNC Start=2113238><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2113396><P Class=ENCC>
the ice industry eventually employed tens of thousands of people.
<SYNC Start=2117672><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2124429><P Class=ENCC>
Tudor became the largest distributor of ice
<SYNC Start=2128382><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2128426><P Class=ENCC>
and he became one of the first American millionaires.
<SYNC Start=2131538><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2131768><P Class=ENCC>
And we're talking about one of his ships going to the Caribbean giving him a profit of $6000.
<SYNC Start=2137244><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2137364><P Class=ENCC>
Now, this is in a time period when people were earning $200 to $300 a year - the average family.
<SYNC Start=2142585><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2142795><P Class=ENCC>
so someone earning thousands of dollars was just inconceivable.
<SYNC Start=2146088><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2146249><P Class=ENCC>
And that would be losing 20 percent of your ice when it got there.
<SYNC Start=2150008><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2150130><P Class=ENCC>
There was still huge amounts of profit.
<SYNC Start=2152209><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2155809><P Class=ENCC>
Tudor's success was based around an extraordinary physical property of ice.
<SYNC Start=2160248><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2160408><P Class=ENCC>
It takes the same amount of heat to melt a block of ice
<SYNC Start=2163376><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2163457><P Class=ENCC>
as it does to heat a similar quantity of water to around 80 degrees centigrade.
<SYNC Start=2168390><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2168676><P Class=ENCC>
This meant that ice took a long time to melt, even when shipped to hotter climates.
<SYNC Start=2174311><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2184294><P Class=ENCC>
What started out as a small family enterprise turned into a global business.
<SYNC Start=2188338><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2188853><P Class=ENCC>
Frederic Tudor had industrialized cold
<SYNC Start=2191740><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2191940><P Class=ENCC>
in the same way the great pioneers of steam had harnessed heat.
<SYNC Start=2195820><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2200139><P Class=ENCC>
By the 1830's, the industrial revolution was in full swing.
<SYNC Start=2204413><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2205630><P Class=ENCC>
Yet ironically, it was not until a small group of scientists worked out
<SYNC Start=2209784><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2209823><P Class=ENCC>
the underlying principles of how steam engines convert heat into motion,
<SYNC Start=2214690><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2214862><P Class=ENCC>
that the next step in the conquest of cold could be made.
<SYNC Start=2218262><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2218666><P Class=ENCC>
Only after solving this riddle of heat engines,
<SYNC Start=2221508><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2221577><P Class=ENCC>
could the first cold engines be made to produce artificial refrigeration.
<SYNC Start=2226862><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2231695><P Class=ENCC>
"How much useful work can you get out of a given amount of heat?"
<SYNC Start=2236893><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2237351><P Class=ENCC>
By the early 1800's, that had become the single most important economic problem in Europe.
<SYNC Start=2244781><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2248643><P Class=ENCC>
To make a profit was to convert heat into motion efficiently
<SYNC Start=2253442><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2253637><P Class=ENCC>
without wasting heat and getting the maximum amount of mechanical effect.
<SYNC Start=2259001><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2267429><P Class=ENCC>
The first person to really engage with this problem
<SYNC Start=2269811><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2269905><P Class=ENCC>
was a young French artillery engineer, Sadi Carnot.
<SYNC Start=2273762><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2274221><P Class=ENCC>
He thought that improving the efficiency of steam engines
<SYNC Start=2277527><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2277588><P Class=ENCC>
might help France's flagging economy after the defeat at Waterloo.
<SYNC Start=2282003><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2282262><P Class=ENCC>
Working at the Conservatoire des Arts et Metiers,
<SYNC Start=2285103><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2285187><P Class=ENCC>
he began to analyze how a steam engine was able to turn heat into mechanical work.
<SYNC Start=2290752><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2293334><P Class=ENCC>
The originality of Carnot's treatment, in my eyes, is essentially that
<SYNC Start=2299754><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2299824><P Class=ENCC>
he shows that in order to extract energy, to extract work from a heat engine,
<SYNC Start=2306034><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2306097><P Class=ENCC>
you need a high temperature source, which is the boiler,
<SYNC Start=2310442><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2310600><P Class=ENCC>
and you need a lower temperature, which is that of the condenser.
<SYNC Start=2314085><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2314326><P Class=ENCC>
And the essence of the heat engine for Carnot is that
<SYNC Start=2317773><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2317825><P Class=ENCC>
heat passes from the high temperature of the boiler
<SYNC Start=2321220><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2321316><P Class=ENCC>
to the lower temperature of the condenser.
<SYNC Start=2324334><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2325516><P Class=ENCC>
In steam engines, it looks as though heat is flowing around the engine,
<SYNC Start=2331986><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2332102><P Class=ENCC>
and as it flows, the engine does mechanical work.
<SYNC Start=2336213><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2341413><P Class=ENCC>
The implication there is that heat is neither consumed nor destroyed.
<SYNC Start=2347278><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2347504><P Class=ENCC>
You simply circulate it around, and it does work.
<SYNC Start=2350834><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2350924><P Class=ENCC>
So there the analogy would be between heat in a steam engine and water in a water wheel.
<SYNC Start=2357654><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2358177><P Class=ENCC>
as though it's the flow of heat that is actually getting the work done in a standard steam engine.
<SYNC Start=2363889><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2366239><P Class=ENCC>
Carnot likened this flow of heat to the flow of water over a water wheel.
<SYNC Start=2370997><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2373487><P Class=ENCC>
He saw that the amount of mechanical work produced depended on how far the water fell.
<SYNC Start=2379254><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2382987><P Class=ENCC>
His novel idea was that steam engines worked in a similar way,
<SYNC Start=2386751><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2386879><P Class=ENCC>
except this fall was a fall in temperature from the hottest to the coldest part of the engine.
<SYNC Start=2392726><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2393471><P Class=ENCC>
The greater the temperature difference, the more work was produced.
<SYNC Start=2397172><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2400277><P Class=ENCC>
Carnot distilled these profound ideas into an accessible book for general readers,
<SYNC Start=2405254><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2405331><P Class=ENCC>
which meant it was largely ignored by scientists instead of being heralded as a classic.
<SYNC Start=2411101><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2413039><P Class=ENCC>
Well this is the book. It's Carnot's only publication,
<SYNC Start=2415742><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2415881><P Class=ENCC>
'Reflections on the Motive Power of Fire' - 1824, a small book, 118 pages only,
<SYNC Start=2422021><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2422276><P Class=ENCC>
published just 600 copies, and in his own lifetime it's virtually unknown.
<SYNC Start=2428377><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2428988><P Class=ENCC>
Twenty years after the publication, William Thomson, the Scottish physicist,
<SYNC Start=2433910><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2434311><P Class=ENCC>
is absolutely intent on finding a copy. He's here in Paris..
<SYNC Start=2438600><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2438879><P Class=ENCC>
and the accounts we have suggest that
<SYNC Start=2440970><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2441058><P Class=ENCC>
he spends a great deal of time visiting book shops..
<SYNC Start=2444747><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2444959><P Class=ENCC>
visiting the bookinistes on the banks of the Seine..
<SYNC Start=2448800><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2449045><P Class=ENCC>
looking, always asking for the book.
<SYNC Start=2451216><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2451474><P Class=ENCC>
And the booksellers tell him they've never even heard of it.
<SYNC Start=2455639><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2460952><P Class=ENCC>
Back then, William Thomson, who would later become Lord Kelvin,
<SYNC Start=2464661><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2464787><P Class=ENCC>
a giant in this new field of thermodynamics, was impressed by Carnot's idea
<SYNC Start=2469900><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2469926><P Class=ENCC>
that the movement of heat produced useful work in the machine.
<SYNC Start=2473913><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2474994><P Class=ENCC>
But when he returned home, he heard about an alternative theory
<SYNC Start=2478456><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2478600><P Class=ENCC>
from a Manchester brewer called James Joule.
<SYNC Start=2482107><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2484217><P Class=ENCC>
Joule had this notion that Carnot was wrong -
<SYNC Start=2487606><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2487718><P Class=ENCC>
that heat wasn't producing work just by its movement,
<SYNC Start=2492606><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2492681><P Class=ENCC>
heat was actually turning into mechanical work,
<SYNC Start=2496157><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2496253><P Class=ENCC>
which is a very strange idea when you think about it.
<SYNC Start=2498938><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2499087><P Class=ENCC>
We're all now used to thinking about energy and how it can take all different forms.
<SYNC Start=2504211><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2504485><P Class=ENCC>
But it was a revolutionary idea that heat and something like mechanical energy were..
<SYNC Start=2511143><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2511293><P Class=ENCC>
at bottom, the same kind of thing.
<SYNC Start=2513316><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2517525><P Class=ENCC>
The experiment that convinced Joule of this was set up in the cellar of his brewery.
<SYNC Start=2522340><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2522518><P Class=ENCC>
It converted mechanical movement into heat, almost like a steam engine in reverse.
<SYNC Start=2528274><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2533530><P Class=ENCC>
He used falling weights to drive paddles around the drum of water.
<SYNC Start=2538632><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2539143><P Class=ENCC>
The friction from this process generated a minute amount of heat.
<SYNC Start=2543559><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2546300><P Class=ENCC>
Only brewers had thermometers accurate enough to register this tiny temperature increase
<SYNC Start=2551447><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2551685><P Class=ENCC>
caused by a measured amount of mechanical work.
<SYNC Start=2555267><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2556245><P Class=ENCC>
Joule's work mattered, because it was the first time
<SYNC Start=2560299><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2560403><P Class=ENCC>
that anyone had convincingly measured
<SYNC Start=2563548><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2563684><P Class=ENCC>
the exchange rate between movement and heat.
<SYNC Start=2568329><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2569696><P Class=ENCC>
He proved the existence of something that converts between heat and motion.
<SYNC Start=2578656><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2579524><P Class=ENCC>
That something was going to be called 'energy'.
<SYNC Start=2583005><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2583163><P Class=ENCC>
And it's for that reason that the basic unit of energy
<SYNC Start=2587018><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2587109><P Class=ENCC>
in the new international system of units is named after him, the Joule.
<SYNC Start=2591589><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2593753><P Class=ENCC>
This apparent contradiction between Joule and Carnot was eventually resolved by Thomson
<SYNC Start=2598777><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2598915><P Class=ENCC>
in what would later become known as the 'laws of thermodynamics'.
<SYNC Start=2603416><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2604086><P Class=ENCC>
The first law, from Joule's work, states that
<SYNC Start=2606893><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2606992><P Class=ENCC>
energy can be converted from one form to another,
<SYNC Start=2610138><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2610178><P Class=ENCC>
but can never be created or destroyed.
<SYNC Start=2614046><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2614727><P Class=ENCC>
The second law, from Carnot's theory, states that
<SYNC Start=2617813><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2617879><P Class=ENCC>
heat flows in one direction only, from hot to cold.
<SYNC Start=2622388><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2647438><P Class=ENCC>
In the second half of the 19th century, this new concept of energy
<SYNC Start=2651203><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2651318><P Class=ENCC>
paved the way for steam power to artificially produce cold.
<SYNC Start=2655959><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2657322><P Class=ENCC>
The flow of heat from hot to cold drives any refrigeration site,
<SYNC Start=2661818><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2661872><P Class=ENCC>
whether it's a modern fridge, or a steam-powered ice making machine.
<SYNC Start=2666380><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2672993><P Class=ENCC>
In the first stage of this cycle, gigantic pistons compress ammonia gas into a hot liquid.
<SYNC Start=2678762><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2680637><P Class=ENCC>
The hot liquefied ammonia is pumped into a condenser..
<SYNC Start=2685067><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2685536><P Class=ENCC>
where it is cooled..
<SYNC Start=2688343><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2689466><P Class=ENCC>
and fed into pipes beneath the water tanks.
<SYNC Start=2693061><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2698024><P Class=ENCC>
In the next stage, the liquid ammonia evaporates, and the temperature drops.
<SYNC Start=2702961><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2704589><P Class=ENCC>
As the ammonia absorbs heat from the surrounding water,
<SYNC Start=2707934><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2708067><P Class=ENCC>
gradually the tanks of water become blocks of ice.
<SYNC Start=2712098><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2715034><P Class=ENCC>
By the 1880's, many towns across America had ice plants like this one,
<SYNC Start=2719575><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2719690><P Class=ENCC>
which could produce 150 tons of ice a day.
<SYNC Start=2723308><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2724595><P Class=ENCC>
For the first time, artificially produced ice was threatening
<SYNC Start=2728324><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2728395><P Class=ENCC>
the natural ice trade created by Frederic Tudor.
<SYNC Start=2732723><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2735810><P Class=ENCC>
America's appetite for ice was insatiable.
<SYNC Start=2738845><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2739578><P Class=ENCC>
Slaughter houses, breweries and food warehouses all needed ice.
<SYNC Start=2744257><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2744509><P Class=ENCC>
Animals were disassembled on production lines in Chicago
<SYNC Start=2747891><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2748033><P Class=ENCC>
and the meat was loaded into ice-cooled box cars to be shipped by railroad.
<SYNC Start=2752728><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2753781><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>.. livestock, on its way to the great meat packing centers of the nation, to markets everywhere,</font>
<SYNC Start=2759165><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2759477><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>food of every sort safely and quickly delivered in refrigerator cars.</font>
<SYNC Start=2764155><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2764876><P Class=ENCC>
From New York to Los Angeles, restaurants were able to serve fresh steaks
<SYNC Start=2769205><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2769257><P Class=ENCC>
thousands of miles from where their meals once roamed.
<SYNC Start=2773505><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2774432><P Class=ENCC>
As fruit and vegetables became available out of season, urban diets improved
<SYNC Start=2779348><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2779475><P Class=ENCC>
making city dwellers the best fed people in the world.
<SYNC Start=2783168><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2785272><P Class=ENCC>
And to keep everything fresh at home,
<SYNC Start=2787105><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2787207><P Class=ENCC>
the ice man made his weekly delivery to re-charge the refrigerator.
<SYNC Start=2791581><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2795602><P Class=ENCC>
Refrigeration makes a tremendous difference in people's lives.
<SYNC Start=2797935><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2798070><P Class=ENCC>
First of all, in their diet, what it's possible for them to eat.
<SYNC Start=2801457><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2801796><P Class=ENCC>
They can go to the store once a week, they don't have to go every day.
<SYNC Start=2804674><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2804971><P Class=ENCC>
They can obtain at that store foods that are from almost anywhere in the world
<SYNC Start=2809101><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2809161><P Class=ENCC>
that have been transported and kept cool, and then they can keep them in their own home.
<SYNC Start=2813242><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2814647><P Class=ENCC>
Eventually the ice man disappeared, as more and more households bought electric fridges.
<SYNC Start=2820287><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2822838><P Class=ENCC>
These used the same basic principles as the old ice making machines.
<SYNC Start=2827168><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2827341><P Class=ENCC>
Heat from the food inside is drained away
<SYNC Start=2829825><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2829874><P Class=ENCC>
by the evaporating coolant and is dumped out the back.
<SYNC Start=2833389><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2833706><P Class=ENCC>
The electric pump drives the cycle of compression, evaporation and condensation.
<SYNC Start=2839331><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2840441><P Class=ENCC>
And that's how the fridge got its hum.
<SYNC Start=2843502><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2845213><P Class=ENCC>
The electric power companies loved refrigerators because they ran all day and all night.
<SYNC Start=2849294><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2849536><P Class=ENCC>
They may not have used that much power for each hour, but they continued to use that.
<SYNC Start=2853390><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2853737><P Class=ENCC>
So, one of the ways that they sold rural electrification
<SYNC Start=2856759><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2856912><P Class=ENCC>
was the possibility of having your own refrigerator.
<SYNC Start=2859585><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2861143><P Class=ENCC>
In the early days, the fridge's icebox was used to freeze water, nothing else.
<SYNC Start=2865597><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2866088><P Class=ENCC>
Freezing was seen as having the same damaging effects as frost.
<SYNC Start=2870051><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2875573><P Class=ENCC>
The man who would change this idea forever
<SYNC Start=2878225><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2878355><P Class=ENCC>
was a scientist and explorer called Clarence Birdseye.
<SYNC Start=2882824><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2883318><P Class=ENCC>
In 1912, Birdseye set off on an expedition to Labrador.
<SYNC Start=2887597><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2889136><P Class=ENCC>
And the temperature dropped to 40 degrees below freezing.
<SYNC Start=2893012><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2902460><P Class=ENCC>
The Inuit had taught Birdseye how to ice fish.
<SYNC Start=2906402><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2908750><P Class=ENCC>
Get a hole in the ice, it could be several feet thick.
<SYNC Start=2911131><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2911349><P Class=ENCC>
And the fish with the pole(???) lying down below, bring the fish up.
<SYNC Start=2914516><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2914765><P Class=ENCC>
And as he'd do that, he found that it would freeze in this terribly cold air
<SYNC Start=2919121><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2919358><P Class=ENCC>
almost before they had it shouldered.
<SYNC Start=2921486><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2923141><P Class=ENCC>
When you went to cook this fish, it tasted just as good as it's fresh.
<SYNC Start=2926980><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2927223><P Class=ENCC>
And he couldn't figure that out, because when he froze fish at home, they would taste terrible.
<SYNC Start=2932854><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2933278><P Class=ENCC>
So when he got back home, he finally tried to figure out
<SYNC Start=2935800><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2935922><P Class=ENCC>
what was the difference between this quick freezing and usual freezing.
<SYNC Start=2940177><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2945546><P Class=ENCC>
Under closer examination, he could see what was happening to the fish cells.
<SYNC Start=2949964><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2952245><P Class=ENCC>
With slow freezing, large ice crystals formed which distorted and ruptured the cells.
<SYNC Start=2958554><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2958969><P Class=ENCC>
When thawed, the tissue collapsed and all the nutrients and flavor washed away.
<SYNC Start=2964125><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2965975><P Class=ENCC>
That's the 'mushy strawberry syndrome'.
<SYNC Start=2967921><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2968127><P Class=ENCC>
People food freeze strawberries as they pick and dry them (???),
<SYNC Start=2971241><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2971395><P Class=ENCC>
then they put them out on the table the next day, and they collapse, they're all mushy.
<SYNC Start=2977268><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2977998><P Class=ENCC>
But with fast freezing, only tiny ice crystals were formed inside the cells
<SYNC Start=2982686><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2982787><P Class=ENCC>
and these caused little damage.
<SYNC Start=2985077><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2985525><P Class=ENCC>
It was all down to the speed of the freezing zone.
<SYNC Start=2988385><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2990394><P Class=ENCC>
What Birdseye found out is, if you can get food to this zone very quickly -
<SYNC Start=2994168><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2994358><P Class=ENCC>
flash freezing or quick freezing,
<SYNC Start=2996127><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=2996468><P Class=ENCC>
you avoid this ice crystallization, and that makes it possible for the food,
<SYNC Start=3001391><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3001517><P Class=ENCC>
when it's unfrozen and cooked, to taste just as good as it's fresh.
<SYNC Start=3005783><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3008110><P Class=ENCC>
The basic concept was simple, but it took Clarence Birdseye another ten years
<SYNC Start=3012936><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3013020><P Class=ENCC>
to perfect the commercial fast-freezing technique
<SYNC Start=3015643><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3015734><P Class=ENCC>
that would mimic the natural process he'd experienced in Labrador.
<SYNC Start=3019759><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3021657><P Class=ENCC>
In 1924, he opened a flash freezing plant in Gloucester, Massachusetts
<SYNC Start=3026274><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3026383><P Class=ENCC>
that froze freshly landed fish at -45 degrees.
<SYNC Start=3030403><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3033283><P Class=ENCC>
He then extended that to all sorts of other kinds of meats and produce and vegetables,
<SYNC Start=3037598><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3037829><P Class=ENCC>
and almost single-handedly invented the frozen food industry.
<SYNC Start=3041884><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3043297><P Class=ENCC>
Fridges and freezers would eventually become icons of modern living.
<SYNC Start=3047144><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3047654><P Class=ENCC>
But there was a less visible cold transformation happening at the same time.
<SYNC Start=3051746><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3052020><P Class=ENCC>
This would also have a huge impact on urban living,
<SYNC Start=3055593><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3056543><P Class=ENCC>
the cooling of the air itself.
<SYNC Start=3059256><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3060822><P Class=ENCC>
Three centuries had passed since Cornelius Drebbel had shaken King James in Westminster.
<SYNC Start=3066476><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3066767><P Class=ENCC>
Now, at the dawn of the 20th century, air cooling was about to shake the world.
<SYNC Start=3072438><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3073584><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Tell me, what is the lowdown on this air conditioning thing?</font>
<SYNC Start=3076897><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3077095><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Now you've started something by asking me that.</font>
<SYNC Start=3079547><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3084476><P Class=ENCC>
Air conditioning was about to transform America.
<SYNC Start=3087365><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3087596><P Class=ENCC>
And the person responsible was Willis Carrier,
<SYNC Start=3090761><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3090922><P Class=ENCC>
whose important breakthrough passed into comfort cooling mythology.
<SYNC Start=3095488><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3097687><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Let's go back to that foggy night,</font>
<SYNC Start=3099383><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3099482><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>when a young engineer named Willis Carrier sought the answer to a problem:</font>
<SYNC Start=3103619><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3103996><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>the effects of humidity of moist air on industrial production.</font>
<SYNC Start=3108343><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3108600><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Fog, maybe that's the answer.</font>
<SYNC Start=3111454><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3112120><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Let's see..</font>
<SYNC Start=3113277><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3113536><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Fog is water vapour that's been condensed.</font>
<SYNC Start=3115770><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3116145><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>That's because the air has become cooler,</font>
<SYNC Start=3118793><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3118826><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>and cool air kept all this much moisture as warm air.</font>
<SYNC Start=3122181><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3122533><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Maybe that's the way to reduce humidity.</font>
<SYNC Start=3124920><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3125059><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Cool the air, and condense the moisture.</font>
<SYNC Start=3128228><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3128807><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>It might work.</font>
<SYNC Start=3130336><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3131244><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Control of humidity through control of temperature.</font>
<SYNC Start=3134231><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3134397><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>That was Willis Carrier's idea.</font>
<SYNC Start=3137475><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3140047><P Class=ENCC>
Carrier is sent to Brooklyn for a very special job in 1902.
<SYNC Start=3145182><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3145996><P Class=ENCC>
The company that publishes the magazine 'Judge',
<SYNC Start=3150348><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3150535><P Class=ENCC>
one of the most popular full-color magazines in America at this particular time,
<SYNC Start=3156715><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3156822><P Class=ENCC>
is having a huge problem.
<SYNC Start=3158350><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3158759><P Class=ENCC>
It's July in Brooklyn, and the ink for which they..
<SYNC Start=3163080><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3163176><P Class=ENCC>
which they use on their beautiful covers is sliding off the pages.
<SYNC Start=3167138><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3167352><P Class=ENCC>
It will not stick because the humidity is too high.
<SYNC Start=3170721><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3173704><P Class=ENCC>
Carrier, using some principles that he's been developing
<SYNC Start=3176828><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3176897><P Class=ENCC>
as a young, new employee of this fan company,
<SYNC Start=3179876><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3180057><P Class=ENCC>
finds a way to get out the July of 1902 run of the Judge magazine,
<SYNC Start=3185713><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3185897><P Class=ENCC>
and from there he begins to eventually build his air conditioning empire.
<SYNC Start=3190611><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3194093><P Class=ENCC>
The demand for air conditioning gradually grew.
<SYNC Start=3197326><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3197796><P Class=ENCC>
In the 1920's, movie houses were among the first to promote the benefits.
<SYNC Start=3202341><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3202975><P Class=ENCC>
People would flock there in summer to shelter from the heat.
<SYNC Start=3206489><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3206878><P Class=ENCC>
The movies are wildly popular.
<SYNC Start=3208964><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3209087><P Class=ENCC>
And the air conditioning certainly helps to attract an audience,
<SYNC Start=3212286><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3212353><P Class=ENCC>
especially if they happen to be walking down the street on a horribly hot day,
<SYNC Start=3215588><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3215661><P Class=ENCC>
and they duck into this movie theater and have this wonderful experience.
<SYNC Start=3218292><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3222952><P Class=ENCC>
Air conditioning became increasingly common in the workplace too,
<SYNC Start=3226519><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3226876><P Class=ENCC>
particularly in the South, where textile and tobacco factories
<SYNC Start=3230519><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3230589><P Class=ENCC>
were almost unbearable without cooling.
<SYNC Start=3233647><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3234991><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>When employees breathe good air and feel comfortable</font>
<SYNC Start=3238017><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3238186><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>they work faster and do a better job.</font>
<SYNC Start=3240635><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3241021><P Class=ENCC>
I think some people think that these were nice, compassionate employers
<SYNC Start=3245348><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3245409><P Class=ENCC>
who were cooling down the workplace for the workers,
<SYNC Start=3247400><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3247426><P Class=ENCC>
but of course nothing could be further from the truth.
<SYNC Start=3249619><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3249886><P Class=ENCC>
That was an inadvertent byproduct, but actually this was..
<SYNC Start=3255027><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3255091><P Class=ENCC>
a quality control device to control the breaking of fibers in cotton mills,
<SYNC Start=3260195><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3260335><P Class=ENCC>
to get consistent quality control in these various industries,
<SYNC Start=3265428><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3265541><P Class=ENCC>
to control the dust that had bedevilled tobacco stemming room workers for decades.
<SYNC Start=3271697><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3272393><P Class=ENCC>
And I think the workers obviously went home and..
<SYNC Start=3276563><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3276674><P Class=ENCC>
to their un-air-conditioned shacks, in most cases..
<SYNC Start=3280235><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3280798><P Class=ENCC>
and talked about how nice and cool it was working during the day.
<SYNC Start=3285318><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3285908><P Class=ENCC>
Well as anybody will tell you who's lived here for very long..
<SYNC Start=3288668><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3288782><P Class=ENCC>
even today, age of air conditioning, there's still plenty of sun, and sweat, and humidity.
<SYNC Start=3294039><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3294166><P Class=ENCC>
It's something you just have to deal with.
<SYNC Start=3295799><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3296201><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>It's silly to suffer from the heat when you can afford the modest cost of air conditioning.</font>
<SYNC Start=3301092><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3301636><P Class=ENCC>
By the 1950's, people were air conditioning their homes
<SYNC Start=3304990><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3305123><P Class=ENCC>
with stand-alone window units that could be easily installed.
<SYNC Start=3308950><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3309416><P Class=ENCC>
This wasn't just an appliance. It offered a new, cool way of life.
<SYNC Start=3314064><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3326387><P Class=ENCC>
Walking down a typical Southern street prior to the air conditioning revolution,
<SYNC Start=3331771><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3332479><P Class=ENCC>
you would've seen families, individuals, outside.
<SYNC Start=3335515><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3335674><P Class=ENCC>
They would've been on their porches, on each other's porches.
<SYNC Start=3338937><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3339046><P Class=ENCC>
There was a visiting tradition, a real sense of community.
<SYNC Start=3342035><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3346070><P Class=ENCC>
Well, I think all that changes with air conditioning, and..
<SYNC Start=3348823><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3349342><P Class=ENCC>
you walk down that same street, and basically what you'll hear are
<SYNC Start=3351511><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3351574><P Class=ENCC>
not the voices of people talking on the porch,
<SYNC Start=3353817><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3353864><P Class=ENCC>
but you'll hear the whir of the compressors.
<SYNC Start=3355731><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3360175><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>Guess what we've got?</font>
<SYNC Start=3361759><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3363085><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>An RCA room air conditioner.</font>
<SYNC Start=3365547><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3365953><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>I'm a woman, and I know how much pure air means to mother</font>
<SYNC Start=3368961><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3369014><P Class=ENCC>
<font color=lightgreen>in keeping our rooms clean and free from dust and dirt.</font>
<SYNC Start=3372628><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3380905><P Class=ENCC>
Control of the cold has transformed city life.
<SYNC Start=3384313><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3386102><P Class=ENCC>
Refrigeration helped cities expand outwards
<SYNC Start=3389150><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3389289><P Class=ENCC>
by enabling large numbers of people to live at great distances from their source of food.
<SYNC Start=3394318><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3399707><P Class=ENCC>
Air conditioning enabled cities to expand upwards.
<SYNC Start=3403687><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3404469><P Class=ENCC>
Beyond 20 stories, high winds make open windows impractical.
<SYNC Start=3408661><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3409435><P Class=ENCC>
But with air conditioning, 100 story skyscrapers were possible.
<SYNC Start=3414260><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3419557><P Class=ENCC>
Technologies emerged which not only worked
<SYNC Start=3423713><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3423900><P Class=ENCC>
to insulate human society against the evils of cold,
<SYNC Start=3428533><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3428701><P Class=ENCC>
but turned cold into a productive, manageable, effective resource.
<SYNC Start=3434741><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3435119><P Class=ENCC>
On the one hand the steam engine, on the other the refrigerator.
<SYNC Start=3439843><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3440165><P Class=ENCC>
Those two great symbols of 19th century world
<SYNC Start=3444283><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3444470><P Class=ENCC>
which completely changed the society and economy of the planet.
<SYNC Start=3449177><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3451011><P Class=ENCC>
All that is part of, I think, what we could call 'bringing cold to market' -
<SYNC Start=3456398><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3456657><P Class=ENCC>
turning it from an evil agent that you feared
<SYNC Start=3459975><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3460182><P Class=ENCC>
into a force of nature from which you could profit.
<SYNC Start=3463972><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3466726><P Class=ENCC>
The explosive growth of the modern world over the last two centuries
<SYNC Start=3470749><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3470872><P Class=ENCC>
owes much to the conquest of cold.
<SYNC Start=3473463><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3473671><P Class=ENCC>
But this is only the beginning of the journey down the temperature scale.
<SYNC Start=3478033><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3478740><P Class=ENCC>
Going lower would be even harder, but would produce greater wonders
<SYNC Start=3483266><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3483355><P Class=ENCC>
that promise extraordinary innovations for the future.
<SYNC Start=3486908><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3488899><P Class=ENCC>
With rival scientists racing towards the final frontier,
<SYNC Start=3492144><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3492290><P Class=ENCC>
the pace quickens and the molecular dance slows,
<SYNC Start=3496420><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3496617><P Class=ENCC>
as they approach the holy grail of cold..
<SYNC Start=3499645><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
<SYNC Start=3499791><P Class=ENCC>
absolute zero.
<SYNC Start=3502160><P Class=ENCC>&nbsp;
</BODY>
</SAMI>